1561 /*************************************************************************
1562 This structure stores optimization report:
1563 * IterationsCount total number of inner iterations
1564 * NFEV number of gradient evaluations
1565 * TerminationType termination type (see below)
1566 
1567 TERMINATION CODES
1568 
1569 TerminationType field contains completion code, which can be:
1570  -8 internal integrity control detected infinite or NAN values in
1571  function/gradient. Abnormal termination signalled.
1572  -7 gradient verification failed.
1573  See MinLBFGSSetGradientCheck() for more information.
1574  1 relative function improvement is no more than EpsF.
1575  2 relative step is no more than EpsX.
1576  4 gradient norm is no more than EpsG
1577  5 MaxIts steps was taken
1578  7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
1579  further improvement is impossible,
1580  X contains best point found so far.
1581  8 terminated by user who called minlbfgsrequesttermination().
1582  X contains point which was "current accepted" when termination
1583  request was submitted.
1584 
1585 Other fields of this structure are not documented and should not be used!
1586 *************************************************************************/
1587 class _minlbfgsreport_owner
1588 {
1589 public:
1594  _minlbfgsreport_owner();
1600  _minlbfgsreport_owner(const _minlbfgsreport_owner &rhs);
1607  _minlbfgsreport_owner& operator=(const _minlbfgsreport_owner &rhs);
1612  virtual ~_minlbfgsreport_owner();
1618  alglib_impl::minlbfgsreport* c_ptr();
1624  alglib_impl::minlbfgsreport* c_ptr() const;
1625 protected:
1626  alglib_impl::minlbfgsreport *p_struct;
1627 };

1949 /*************************************************************************

1951 * IterationsCount number of iterations
1952 * NFEV number of gradient evaluations
1953 * TerminationType termination type (see below)
1954 
1955 TERMINATION CODES
1956 
1957 TerminationType field contains completion code, which can be:
1958  -8 internal integrity control detected infinite or NAN values in
1959  function/gradient. Abnormal termination signalled.
1960  -7 gradient verification failed.
1961  See MinBLEICSetGradientCheck() for more information.
1962  -3 inconsistent constraints. Feasible point is
1963  either nonexistent or too hard to find. Try to
1964  restart optimizer with better initial approximation
1965  1 relative function improvement is no more than EpsF.
1966  2 relative step is no more than EpsX.
1967  4 gradient norm is no more than EpsG
1968  5 MaxIts steps was taken
1969  7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
1970  further improvement is impossible,
1971  X contains best point found so far.
1972  8 terminated by user who called minbleicrequesttermination(). X contains
1973  point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
1974  submitted.
1975 
1976 ADDITIONAL FIELDS
1977 
1978 There are additional fields which can be used for debugging:
1979 * DebugEqErr error in the equality constraints (2-norm)
1980 * DebugFS f, calculated at projection of initial point
1981  to the feasible set
1982 * DebugFF f, calculated at the final point
1983 * DebugDX |X_start-X_final|
1984 *************************************************************************/

2179  try to restart optimizer with better initial approximation.

3252 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINLBFGS) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
3253 /*************************************************************************
3254  LIMITED MEMORY BFGS METHOD FOR LARGE SCALE OPTIMIZATION
3255 
3256 DESCRIPTION:
3257 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments by using a quasi-
3258 Newton method (LBFGS scheme) which is optimized to use a minimum amount
3259 of memory.
3260 The subroutine generates the approximation of an inverse Hessian matrix by
3261 using information about the last M steps of the algorithm (instead of N).
3262 It lessens a required amount of memory from a value of order N^2 to a
3263 value of order 2*N*M.
3264 
3265 
3266 REQUIREMENTS:
3267 Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
3268 * function value F and its gradient G (simultaneously) at given point X
3269 
3270 
3271 USAGE:
3272 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinLBFGSCreate() call
3273 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinLBFGSSetCond() MinLBFGSSetStpMax()
3274  and other functions
3275 3. User calls MinLBFGSOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
3276  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
3277 4. User calls MinLBFGSResults() to get solution
3278 5. Optionally user may call MinLBFGSRestartFrom() to solve another problem
3279  with same N/M but another starting point and/or another function.
3280  MinLBFGSRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
3281 
3282 
3283 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3284  N - problem dimension. N>0
3285  M - number of corrections in the BFGS scheme of Hessian
3286  approximation update. Recommended value: 3<=M<=7. The smaller
3287  value causes worse convergence, the bigger will not cause a
3288  considerably better convergence, but will cause a fall in the
3289  performance. M<=N.
3290  X - initial solution approximation, array[0..N-1].
3291 
3292 
3293 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3294  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3295 
3296 
3297 NOTES:
3298 1. you may tune stopping conditions with MinLBFGSSetCond() function
3299 2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
3300  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
3301  use MinLBFGSSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps. However,
3302  L-BFGS rarely needs such a tuning.
3303 
3304 
3305  -- ALGLIB --
3306  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
3307 *************************************************************************/
3308 void minlbfgscreate(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlbfgsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3309 void minlbfgscreate(const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlbfgsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3310 
3311 
3312 /*************************************************************************
3313 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinLBFGSCreate(). It uses
3314 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
3315 
3316 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
3317 only. We recommend to read comments on MinLBFGSCreate() in order to get
3318 more information about creation of LBFGS optimizer.
3319 
3320 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3321  N - problem dimension, N>0:
3322  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
3323  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
3324  M - number of corrections in the BFGS scheme of Hessian
3325  approximation update. Recommended value: 3<=M<=7. The smaller
3326  value causes worse convergence, the bigger will not cause a
3327  considerably better convergence, but will cause a fall in the
3328  performance. M<=N.
3329  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
3330  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
3331 
3332 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3333  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3334 
3335 NOTES:
3336 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
3337 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
3338  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinLBFGSSetScale() call.
3339 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
3340  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
3341  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
3342  value to start with.
3343 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
3344  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
3345  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
3346  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
3347  small ones.
3348  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
3349  is less robust and precise. LBFGS needs exact gradient values.
3350  Imprecise gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly
3351  nonlinear problems.
3352  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
3353  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
3354  as possible.
3355 
3356  -- ALGLIB --
3357  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3358 *************************************************************************/
3359 void minlbfgscreatef(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minlbfgsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3360 void minlbfgscreatef(const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minlbfgsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3361 
3362 
3363 /*************************************************************************
3364 This function sets stopping conditions for L-BFGS optimization algorithm.
3365 
3366 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3367  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3368  EpsG - >=0
3369  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
3370  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
3371  * |.| means Euclidian norm
3372  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
3373  * g - gradient
3374  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLBFGSSetScale()
3375  EpsF - >=0
3376  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3377  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
3378  is satisfied.
3379  EpsX - >=0
3380  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3381  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
3382  * |.| means Euclidian norm
3383  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
3384  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
3385  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLBFGSSetScale()
3386  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
3387  iterations is unlimited.
3388 
3389 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0, EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to
3390 automatic stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
3391 
3392  -- ALGLIB --
3393  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
3394 *************************************************************************/
3395 void minlbfgssetcond(const minlbfgsstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3412 void minlbfgssetxrep(const minlbfgsstate &state, const bool needxrep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3415 /*************************************************************************
3416 This function sets maximum step length
3417 
3418 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3419  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3420  StpMax - maximum step length, >=0. Set StpMax to 0.0 (default), if
3421  you don't want to limit step length.
3422 
3423 Use this subroutine when you optimize target function which contains exp()
3424 or other fast growing functions, and optimization algorithm makes too
3425 large steps which leads to overflow. This function allows us to reject
3426 steps that are too large (and therefore expose us to the possible
3427 overflow) without actually calculating function value at the x+stp*d.

3429  -- ALGLIB --

3431 *************************************************************************/
3432 void minlbfgssetstpmax(const minlbfgsstate &state, const double stpmax, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3434 
3435 /*************************************************************************
3436 This function sets scaling coefficients for LBFGS optimizer.
3437 
3438 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
3439 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
3440 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
3441 a) "how large" the variable is
3442 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
3443 
3444 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
3445 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
3446 
3447 In most optimizers (and in the LBFGS too) scaling is NOT a form of
3448 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
3449 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinLBFGSSetPrec...()
3450 functions.
3451 
3452 There is special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
3453 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
3454 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
3455 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
3456 forms of tuning solver.
3457 
3458 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3459  State - structure stores algorithm state
3460  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
3461  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
3462 
3463  -- ALGLIB --
3464  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3465 *************************************************************************/
3466 void minlbfgssetscale(const minlbfgsstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3467

3471 scaling, same for all elements of X) is used.
3472 
3473 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3474  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3475 
3476 NOTE: you can change preconditioner "on the fly", during algorithm
3477 iterations.

3489 INPUT PARAMETERS:

3492  the approximate Hessian. array[0..N-1,0..N-1],
3493  (if larger, only leading N elements are used).
3494  IsUpper - whether upper or lower triangle of P is given
3495  (other triangle is not referenced)
3496 
3497 After call to this function preconditioner is changed to P (P is copied
3498 into the internal buffer).

3500 NOTE: you can change preconditioner "on the fly", during algorithm

3533 /*************************************************************************
3534 Modification of the preconditioner: scale-based diagonal preconditioning.
3535 
3536 This preconditioning mode can be useful when you don't have approximate
3537 diagonal of Hessian, but you know that your variables are badly scaled
3538 (for example, one variable is in [1,10], and another in [1000,100000]),
3539 and most part of the ill-conditioning comes from different scales of vars.
3540 
3541 In this case simple scale-based preconditioner, with H[i] = 1/(s[i]^2),
3542 can greatly improve convergence.
3543 
3544 IMPRTANT: you should set scale of your variables with MinLBFGSSetScale()
3545 call (before or after MinLBFGSSetPrecScale() call). Without knowledge of
3546 the scale of your variables scale-based preconditioner will be just unit
3547 matrix.
3548 
3549 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3550  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3551 
3552  -- ALGLIB --
3553  Copyright 13.10.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey

3566 /*************************************************************************
3567 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
3568 
3569 These functions accept following parameters:
3570  state - algorithm state
3571  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
3572  value func at given point x
3573  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
3574  value func and gradient grad at given point x
3575  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
3576  can be NULL
3577  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
3578  can be NULL
3579 
3580 NOTES:
3581 
3582 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
3583  (analytical) user-supplied gradient, and one which uses function value
3584  only and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
3585  gradient.
3586 
3587  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
3588  (either MinLBFGSCreate() for analytical gradient or MinLBFGSCreateF()
3589  for numerical differentiation) you should choose appropriate variant of
3590  MinLBFGSOptimize() - one which accepts function AND gradient or one
3591  which accepts function ONLY.
3592 
3593  Be careful to choose variant of MinLBFGSOptimize() which corresponds to
3594  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
3595  callback (function/gradient) passed to MinLBFGSOptimize() and specific
3596  function used to create optimizer.
3597 
3598 
3599  | USER PASSED TO MinLBFGSOptimize()
3600  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
3601  ------------------------------------------------------------
3602  MinLBFGSCreateF() | work FAIL
3603  MinLBFGSCreate() | FAIL work
3604 
3605  Here "FAIL" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
3606  function and MinLBFGSOptimize() version. Attemps to use such
3607  combination (for example, to create optimizer with MinLBFGSCreateF() and
3608  to pass gradient information to MinCGOptimize()) will lead to exception
3609  being thrown. Either you did not pass gradient when it WAS needed or
3610  you passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
3611 
3612  -- ALGLIB --
3613  Copyright 20.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
3614 
3615 *************************************************************************/
3616 void minlbfgsoptimize(minlbfgsstate &state,

3618  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,
3619  void *ptr = NULL,
3620  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3654  termination signalled.

3661  EpsF.

3710 /*************************************************************************
3711 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
3712 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
3713 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
3714 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
3715 submitted and returns error code 8 (successful termination).
3716 
3717 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3718  State - optimizer structure
3719 
3720 NOTE: after request for termination optimizer may perform several
3721  additional calls to user-supplied callbacks. It does NOT guarantee
3722  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
3723  will be discarded later.
3724 
3725 NOTE: calling this function on optimizer which is NOT running will have no
3726  effect.
3727 
3728 NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
3729  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
3730 
3731  -- ALGLIB --
3732  Copyright 08.10.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
3733 *************************************************************************/
3734 void minlbfgsrequesttermination(const minlbfgsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3735 
3736 
3737 /*************************************************************************
3738 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
3739 gradient:
3740 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
3741 * MinLBFGSOptimize() is called
3742 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
3743  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
3744  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
3745  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
3746  of i-th parameter
3747  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
3748  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
3749  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
3750  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
3751  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
3752  point
3753  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
3754  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
3755  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
3756 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
3757 
3758 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
3759  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
3760  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
3761  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
3762  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
3763  some third party).
3764 
3765 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
3766  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
3767  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
3768  parameters by means of setting scale with MinLBFGSSetScale().
3769 
3770 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
3771  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
3772  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
3773  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
3774  function.
3775 
3776 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3777  State - structure used to store algorithm state
3778  TestStep - verification step:
3779  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
3780  * TestStep>0 activates verification
3781 
3782  -- ALGLIB --
3783  Copyright 24.05.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
3784 *************************************************************************/
3785 void minlbfgssetgradientcheck(const minlbfgsstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3786 #endif
3787 
3788 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_QPDENSEAULSOLVER) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
3789 
3790 #endif
3791 
3792 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINCG) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
3793 /*************************************************************************
3794  NONLINEAR CONJUGATE GRADIENT METHOD
3795 
3796 DESCRIPTION:
3797 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments by using one of the
3798 nonlinear conjugate gradient methods.
3799 
3800 These CG methods are globally convergent (even on non-convex functions) as
3801 long as grad(f) is Lipschitz continuous in a some neighborhood of the
3802 L = { x : f(x)<=f(x0) }.
3803 
3804 
3805 REQUIREMENTS:
3806 Algorithm will request following information during its operation:
3807 * function value F and its gradient G (simultaneously) at given point X
3808 
3809 
3810 USAGE:
3811 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinCGCreate() call
3812 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinCGSetCond(), MinCGSetStpMax() and
3813  other functions
3814 3. User calls MinCGOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
3815  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
3816 4. User calls MinCGResults() to get solution
3817 5. Optionally, user may call MinCGRestartFrom() to solve another problem
3818  with same N but another starting point and/or another function.
3819  MinCGRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
3820 
3821 
3822 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3823  N - problem dimension, N>0:
3824  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
3825  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
3826  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
3827 
3828 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3829  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3830 
3831  -- ALGLIB --
3832  Copyright 25.03.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
3833 *************************************************************************/
3834 void mincgcreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, mincgstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3835 void mincgcreate(const real_1d_array &x, mincgstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3837 
3838 /*************************************************************************
3839 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinCGCreate(). It uses
3840 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
3841 
3842 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
3843 only. We recommend to read comments on MinCGCreate() in order to get more
3844 information about creation of CG optimizer.
3845 
3846 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3847  N - problem dimension, N>0:
3848  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
3849  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
3850  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
3851  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
3852 
3853 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3854  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3855 
3856 NOTES:
3857 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
3858 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
3859  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinCGSetScale() call.
3860 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
3861  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
3862  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
3863  value to start with.
3864 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
3865  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
3866  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
3867  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
3868  small ones.
3869  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
3870  is less robust and precise. L-BFGS needs exact gradient values.
3871  Imprecise gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly
3872  nonlinear problems.
3873  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
3874  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
3875  as possible.
3876 
3877  -- ALGLIB --
3878  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3879 *************************************************************************/
3880 void mincgcreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, mincgstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3881 void mincgcreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, mincgstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3882 
3883 
3884 /*************************************************************************
3885 This function sets stopping conditions for CG optimization algorithm.
3886 
3887 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3888  State - structure which stores algorithm state
3889  EpsG - >=0
3890  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
3891  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
3892  * |.| means Euclidian norm
3893  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
3894  * g - gradient
3895  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinCGSetScale()
3896  EpsF - >=0
3897  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3898  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
3899  is satisfied.
3900  EpsX - >=0
3901  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
3902  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
3903  * |.| means Euclidian norm
3904  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
3905  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
3906  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinCGSetScale()
3907  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
3908  iterations is unlimited.
3909 
3910 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0, EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to
3911 automatic stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
3912 
3913  -- ALGLIB --
3914  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
3915 *************************************************************************/
3916 void mincgsetcond(const mincgstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3917 
3918 
3919 /*************************************************************************
3920 This function sets scaling coefficients for CG optimizer.
3921 
3922 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
3923 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
3924 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
3925 a) "how large" the variable is
3926 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
3927 
3928 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of CG optimizer - step
3929 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
3930 
3931 In most optimizers (and in the CG too) scaling is NOT a form of
3932 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
3933 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinCGSetPrec...() functions.
3934 
3935 There is special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
3936 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
3937 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
3938 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
3939 forms of tuning solver.
3940 
3941 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3942  State - structure stores algorithm state
3943  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
3944  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
3945 
3946  -- ALGLIB --
3947  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
3948 *************************************************************************/
3949 void mincgsetscale(const mincgstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4003 
4004 /*************************************************************************
4005 This function allows to suggest initial step length to the CG algorithm.
4006 
4007 Suggested step length is used as starting point for the line search. It
4008 can be useful when you have badly scaled problem, i.e. when ||grad||
4009 (which is used as initial estimate for the first step) is many orders of
4010 magnitude different from the desired step.
4011 
4012 Line search may fail on such problems without good estimate of initial
4013 step length. Imagine, for example, problem with ||grad||=10^50 and desired
4014 step equal to 0.1 Line search function will use 10^50 as initial step,
4015 then it will decrease step length by 2 (up to 20 attempts) and will get
4016 10^44, which is still too large.
4017 
4018 This function allows us to tell than line search should be started from
4019 some moderate step length, like 1.0, so algorithm will be able to detect
4020 desired step length in a several searches.
4021 
4022 Default behavior (when no step is suggested) is to use preconditioner, if
4023 it is available, to generate initial estimate of step length.
4024 
4025 This function influences only first iteration of algorithm. It should be
4026 called between MinCGCreate/MinCGRestartFrom() call and MinCGOptimize call.
4027 Suggested step is ignored if you have preconditioner.
4028 
4029 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4030  State - structure used to store algorithm state.
4031  Stp - initial estimate of the step length.
4032  Can be zero (no estimate).
4033 
4034  -- ALGLIB --
4035  Copyright 30.07.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4036 *************************************************************************/
4037 void mincgsuggeststep(const mincgstate &state, const double stp, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4038

4047 iterations.

4077 /*************************************************************************
4078 Modification of the preconditioner: scale-based diagonal preconditioning.
4079 
4080 This preconditioning mode can be useful when you don't have approximate
4081 diagonal of Hessian, but you know that your variables are badly scaled
4082 (for example, one variable is in [1,10], and another in [1000,100000]),
4083 and most part of the ill-conditioning comes from different scales of vars.
4084 
4085 In this case simple scale-based preconditioner, with H[i] = 1/(s[i]^2),
4086 can greatly improve convergence.
4087 
4088 IMPRTANT: you should set scale of your variables with MinCGSetScale() call
4089 (before or after MinCGSetPrecScale() call). Without knowledge of the scale
4090 of your variables scale-based preconditioner will be just unit matrix.
4091

4094 
4095 NOTE: you can change preconditioner "on the fly", during algorithm
4096 iterations.

4112 /*************************************************************************
4113 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
4114 
4115 These functions accept following parameters:
4116  state - algorithm state
4117  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
4118  value func at given point x
4119  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
4120  value func and gradient grad at given point x
4121  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
4122  can be NULL
4123  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
4124  can be NULL
4125 
4126 NOTES:
4127 
4128 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
4129  (analytical) user-supplied gradient, and one which uses function value
4130  only and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
4131  gradient.
4132 
4133  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
4134  (either MinCGCreate() for analytical gradient or MinCGCreateF() for
4135  numerical differentiation) you should choose appropriate variant of
4136  MinCGOptimize() - one which accepts function AND gradient or one which
4137  accepts function ONLY.
4138 
4139  Be careful to choose variant of MinCGOptimize() which corresponds to
4140  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
4141  callback (function/gradient) passed to MinCGOptimize() and specific
4142  function used to create optimizer.
4143 
4144 
4145  | USER PASSED TO MinCGOptimize()
4146  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
4147  ------------------------------------------------------------
4148  MinCGCreateF() | work FAIL
4149  MinCGCreate() | FAIL work
4150 
4151  Here "FAIL" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
4152  function and MinCGOptimize() version. Attemps to use such combination
4153  (for example, to create optimizer with MinCGCreateF() and to pass
4154  gradient information to MinCGOptimize()) will lead to exception being
4155  thrown. Either you did not pass gradient when it WAS needed or you
4156  passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
4157 
4158  -- ALGLIB --
4159  Copyright 20.04.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
4160 
4161 *************************************************************************/

4165  void *ptr = NULL,
4166  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4252 /*************************************************************************
4253 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
4254 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
4255 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
4256 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
4257 submitted and returns error code 8 (successful termination).
4258

4263  additional calls to user-supplied callbacks. It does NOT guarantee
4264  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
4265  will be discarded later.

4268  effect.

4271  subsequent calls are silently ignored.

4276 void mincgrequesttermination(const mincgstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4278 
4279 /*************************************************************************
4280 
4281 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
4282 gradient:
4283 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
4284 * MinCGOptimize() is called
4285 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
4286  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
4287  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
4288  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
4289  of i-th parameter
4290  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
4291  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
4292  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
4293  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
4294  point
4295  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
4296  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
4297  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
4298 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
4299 
4300 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
4301  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
4302  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
4303  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
4304  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
4305  some third party).
4306 
4307 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
4308  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
4309  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
4310  parameters by means of setting scale with MinCGSetScale().
4311 
4312 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
4313  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
4314  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
4315  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
4316  function.
4317 
4318 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4319  State - structure used to store algorithm state
4320  TestStep - verification step:
4321  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
4322  * TestStep>0 activates verification
4323 
4324  -- ALGLIB --
4325  Copyright 31.05.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
4326 *************************************************************************/
4327 void mincgsetgradientcheck(const mincgstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4328 #endif
4329 
4330 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINBLEIC) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
4331 /*************************************************************************
4332  BOUND CONSTRAINED OPTIMIZATION
4333  WITH ADDITIONAL LINEAR EQUALITY AND INEQUALITY CONSTRAINTS
4334 
4335 DESCRIPTION:
4336 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments subject to any
4337 combination of:
4338 * bound constraints
4339 * linear inequality constraints
4340 * linear equality constraints
4341 
4342 REQUIREMENTS:
4343 * user must provide function value and gradient
4344 * starting point X0 must be feasible or
4345  not too far away from the feasible set
4346 * grad(f) must be Lipschitz continuous on a level set:
4347  L = { x : f(x)<=f(x0) }
4348 * function must be defined everywhere on the feasible set F
4349 
4350 USAGE:
4351 
4352 Constrained optimization if far more complex than the unconstrained one.
4353 Here we give very brief outline of the BLEIC optimizer. We strongly recommend
4354 you to read examples in the ALGLIB Reference Manual and to read ALGLIB User Guide
4355 on optimization, which is available at http://www.alglib.net/optimization/
4356 
4357 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinBLEICCreate() call
4358 
4359 2. USer adds boundary and/or linear constraints by calling
4360  MinBLEICSetBC() and MinBLEICSetLC() functions.
4361 
4362 3. User sets stopping conditions with MinBLEICSetCond().
4363 
4364 4. User calls MinBLEICOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
4365  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
4366 
4367 5. User calls MinBLEICResults() to get solution
4368 
4369 6. Optionally user may call MinBLEICRestartFrom() to solve another problem
4370  with same N but another starting point.
4371  MinBLEICRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
4372 
4373 NOTE: if you have box-only constraints (no general linear constraints),
4374  then MinBC optimizer can be better option. It uses special, faster
4375  constraint activation method, which performs better on problems with
4376  multiple constraints active at the solution.
4377 
4378  On small-scale problems performance of MinBC is similar to that of
4379  MinBLEIC, but on large-scale ones (hundreds and thousands of active
4380  constraints) it can be several times faster than MinBLEIC.
4381 
4382 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4383  N - problem dimension, N>0:
4384  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
4385  * if not given, automatically determined from size ofX
4386  X - starting point, array[N]:
4387  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
4388  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
4389  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
4390  approximation.
4391 
4392 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
4393  State - structure stores algorithm state
4394 
4395  -- ALGLIB --
4396  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4397 *************************************************************************/
4398 void minbleiccreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minbleicstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4399 void minbleiccreate(const real_1d_array &x, minbleicstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4400 
4401 
4402 /*************************************************************************
4403 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinBLEICCreate(). It uses
4404 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
4405 
4406 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
4407 only. We recommend to read comments on MinBLEICCreate() in order to get
4408 more information about creation of BLEIC optimizer.
4409 
4410 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4411  N - problem dimension, N>0:
4412  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
4413  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
4414  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
4415  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
4416 
4417 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
4418  State - structure which stores algorithm state
4419 
4420 NOTES:
4421 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
4422 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
4423  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinBLEICSetScale() call.
4424 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
4425  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
4426  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
4427  value to start with.
4428 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
4429  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
4430  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
4431  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
4432  small ones.
4433  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
4434  is less robust and precise. CG needs exact gradient values. Imprecise
4435  gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly nonlinear
4436  problems.
4437  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
4438  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
4439  as possible.
4440 
4441  -- ALGLIB --
4442  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
4443 *************************************************************************/
4444 void minbleiccreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minbleicstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4445 void minbleiccreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minbleicstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4447 
4448 /*************************************************************************
4449 This function sets boundary constraints for BLEIC optimizer.
4450 
4451 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
4452 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinBLEICRestartFrom().
4453 
4454 NOTE: if you have box-only constraints (no general linear constraints),
4455  then MinBC optimizer can be better option. It uses special, faster
4456  constraint activation method, which performs better on problems with
4457  multiple constraints active at the solution.
4458 
4459  On small-scale problems performance of MinBC is similar to that of
4460  MinBLEIC, but on large-scale ones (hundreds and thousands of active
4461  constraints) it can be several times faster than MinBLEIC.
4462 
4463 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4464  State - structure stores algorithm state
4465  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
4466  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
4467  very small number or -INF.
4468  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
4469  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
4470  very large number or +INF.
4471 
4472 NOTE 1: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
4473 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
4474 
4475 NOTE 2: this solver has following useful properties:
4476 * bound constraints are always satisfied exactly
4477 * function is evaluated only INSIDE area specified by bound constraints,
4478  even when numerical differentiation is used (algorithm adjusts nodes
4479  according to boundary constraints)
4480 
4481  -- ALGLIB --
4482  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4483 *************************************************************************/
4484 void minbleicsetbc(const minbleicstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4485 
4486 
4487 /*************************************************************************
4488 This function sets linear constraints for BLEIC optimizer.
4489 
4490 Linear constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
4491 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinBLEICRestartFrom().
4492 
4493 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4494  State - structure previously allocated with MinBLEICCreate call.
4495  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
4496  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
4497  or inequality (see below):
4498  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
4499  * last element corresponds to the right part.
4500  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
4501  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
4502  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
4503  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
4504  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
4505  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
4506  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
4507  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
4508 
4509 NOTE 1: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately:
4510 * there always exists some minor violation (about Epsilon in magnitude)
4511  due to rounding errors
4512 * numerical differentiation, if used, may lead to function evaluations
4513  outside of the feasible area, because algorithm does NOT change
4514  numerical differentiation formula according to linear constraints.
4515 If you want constraints to be satisfied exactly, try to reformulate your
4516 problem in such manner that all constraints will become boundary ones
4517 (this kind of constraints is always satisfied exactly, both in the final
4518 solution and in all intermediate points).
4519 
4520  -- ALGLIB --
4521  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4522 *************************************************************************/
4523 void minbleicsetlc(const minbleicstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
4524 void minbleicsetlc(const minbleicstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4526 
4527 /*************************************************************************
4528 This function sets stopping conditions for the optimizer.
4529 
4530 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4531  State - structure which stores algorithm state
4532  EpsG - >=0
4533  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
4534  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
4535  * |.| means Euclidian norm
4536  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
4537  * g - gradient
4538  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBLEICSetScale()
4539  EpsF - >=0
4540  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
4541  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
4542  is satisfied.
4543  EpsX - >=0
4544  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
4545  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
4546  * |.| means Euclidian norm
4547  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
4548  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
4549  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBLEICSetScale()
4550  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
4551  iterations is unlimited.
4552 
4553 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
4554 to automatic stopping criterion selection.
4555 
4556 NOTE: when SetCond() called with non-zero MaxIts, BLEIC solver may perform
4557  slightly more than MaxIts iterations. I.e., MaxIts sets non-strict
4558  limit on iterations count.
4559 
4560  -- ALGLIB --
4561  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4562 *************************************************************************/
4563 void minbleicsetcond(const minbleicstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4565 
4566 /*************************************************************************
4567 This function sets scaling coefficients for BLEIC optimizer.
4568 
4569 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
4570 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
4571 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
4572 a) "how large" the variable is
4573 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
4574 
4575 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
4576 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
4577 
4578 In most optimizers (and in the BLEIC too) scaling is NOT a form of
4579 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
4580 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinBLEICSetPrec...()
4581 functions.
4582 
4583 There is a special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
4584 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
4585 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
4586 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
4587 forms of tuning solver.
4588 
4589 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4590  State - structure stores algorithm state
4591  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
4592  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
4593 
4594  -- ALGLIB --
4595  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
4596 *************************************************************************/
4597 void minbleicsetscale(const minbleicstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4631 /*************************************************************************
4632 Modification of the preconditioner: scale-based diagonal preconditioning.
4633 
4634 This preconditioning mode can be useful when you don't have approximate
4635 diagonal of Hessian, but you know that your variables are badly scaled
4636 (for example, one variable is in [1,10], and another in [1000,100000]),
4637 and most part of the ill-conditioning comes from different scales of vars.
4638 
4639 In this case simple scale-based preconditioner, with H[i] = 1/(s[i]^2),
4640 can greatly improve convergence.
4641 
4642 IMPRTANT: you should set scale of your variables with MinBLEICSetScale()
4643 call (before or after MinBLEICSetPrecScale() call). Without knowledge of
4644 the scale of your variables scale-based preconditioner will be just unit
4645 matrix.
4646 
4647 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4648  State - structure which stores algorithm state
4649 
4650  -- ALGLIB --
4651  Copyright 13.10.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey

4676 set upper limit on step length, when you solve optimization problem with
4677 linear (non-boundary) constraints AND preconditioner turned on.
4678 
4679 When non-boundary constraints are present, you have to either a) use
4680 preconditioner, or b) use upper limit on step length. YOU CAN'T USE BOTH!
4681 In this case algorithm will terminate with appropriate error code.

4689 or other fast growing functions, and optimization algorithm makes too

4708 /*************************************************************************
4709 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
4710 
4711 These functions accept following parameters:
4712  state - algorithm state
4713  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
4714  value func at given point x
4715  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
4716  value func and gradient grad at given point x
4717  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
4718  can be NULL
4719  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
4720  can be NULL
4721 
4722 NOTES:
4723 
4724 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
4725  (analytical) user-supplied gradient, and one which uses function value
4726  only and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
4727  gradient.
4728 
4729  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
4730  (either MinBLEICCreate() for analytical gradient or MinBLEICCreateF()
4731  for numerical differentiation) you should choose appropriate variant of
4732  MinBLEICOptimize() - one which accepts function AND gradient or one
4733  which accepts function ONLY.
4734 
4735  Be careful to choose variant of MinBLEICOptimize() which corresponds to
4736  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
4737  callback (function/gradient) passed to MinBLEICOptimize() and specific
4738  function used to create optimizer.
4739 
4740 
4741  | USER PASSED TO MinBLEICOptimize()
4742  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
4743  ------------------------------------------------------------
4744  MinBLEICCreateF() | work FAIL
4745  MinBLEICCreate() | FAIL work
4746 
4747  Here "FAIL" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
4748  function and MinBLEICOptimize() version. Attemps to use such
4749  combination (for example, to create optimizer with MinBLEICCreateF()
4750  and to pass gradient information to MinCGOptimize()) will lead to
4751  exception being thrown. Either you did not pass gradient when it WAS
4752  needed or you passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
4753 
4754  -- ALGLIB --
4755  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
4756 
4757 *************************************************************************/

4761  void *ptr = NULL,
4762  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4850 /*************************************************************************
4851 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
4852 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
4853 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
4854 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was

4862  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
4863  will be discarded later.

4866  effect.

4877 /*************************************************************************
4878 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
4879 gradient:
4880 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
4881 * MinBLEICOptimize() is called
4882 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
4883  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
4884  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
4885  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
4886  of i-th parameter
4887  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
4888  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
4889  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
4890  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
4891  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
4892  point
4893  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
4894  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
4895  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
4896 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
4897 
4898 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
4899  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
4900  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
4901  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
4902  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
4903  some third party).
4904 
4905 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
4906  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
4907  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
4908  parameters by means of setting scale with MinBLEICSetScale().
4909 
4910 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
4911  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
4912  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
4913  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
4914  function.
4915 
4916 INPUT PARAMETERS:
4917  State - structure used to store algorithm state
4918  TestStep - verification step:
4919  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
4920  * TestStep>0 activates verification
4921 
4922  -- ALGLIB --
4923  Copyright 15.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
4924 *************************************************************************/
4925 void minbleicsetgradientcheck(const minbleicstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4942 criteria by means of MinQPSetAlgo??????() function. Then, you should start
4943 solution process by means of MinQPOptimize() call. Solution itself can be
4944 obtained with MinQPResults() function.

4946 Following solvers are recommended:
4947 * QuickQP for dense problems with box-only constraints (or no constraints

4982 /*************************************************************************
4983 This function sets dense quadratic term for QP solver. By default,
4984 quadratic term is zero.
4985 
4986 SUPPORT BY QP SOLVERS:
4987 
4988 Dense quadratic term can be handled by following QP solvers:
4989 * QuickQP
4990 * BLEIC-QP
4991 * Dense-AUL-QP
4992 
4993 IMPORTANT:
4994 
4995 This solver minimizes following function:
4996  f(x) = 0.5*x'*A*x + b'*x.
4997 Note that quadratic term has 0.5 before it. So if you want to minimize
4998  f(x) = x^2 + x
4999 you should rewrite your problem as follows:
5000  f(x) = 0.5*(2*x^2) + x
5001 and your matrix A will be equal to [[2.0]], not to [[1.0]]
5002 
5003 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5004  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5005  A - matrix, array[N,N]
5006  IsUpper - (optional) storage type:
5007  * if True, symmetric matrix A is given by its upper
5008  triangle, and the lower triangle isn't used
5009  * if False, symmetric matrix A is given by its lower
5010  triangle, and the upper triangle isn't used
5011  * if not given, both lower and upper triangles must be
5012  filled.
5013 
5014  -- ALGLIB --
5015  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5016 *************************************************************************/
5017 void minqpsetquadraticterm(const minqpstate &state, const real_2d_array &a, const bool isupper, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5018 void minqpsetquadraticterm(const minqpstate &state, const real_2d_array &a, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5019 
5020 
5021 /*************************************************************************
5022 This function sets sparse quadratic term for QP solver. By default,
5023 quadratic term is zero. This function overrides previous calls to
5024 minqpsetquadraticterm() or minqpsetquadratictermsparse().
5025 
5026 SUPPORT BY QP SOLVERS:
5027 
5028 Sparse quadratic term can be handled by following QP solvers:
5029 * QuickQP
5030 * BLEIC-QP
5031 * Dense-AUL-QP (internally converts sparse matrix to dense format)
5032 
5033 IMPORTANT:
5034 
5035 This solver minimizes following function:
5036  f(x) = 0.5*x'*A*x + b'*x.
5037 Note that quadratic term has 0.5 before it. So if you want to minimize
5038  f(x) = x^2 + x
5039 you should rewrite your problem as follows:
5040  f(x) = 0.5*(2*x^2) + x
5041 and your matrix A will be equal to [[2.0]], not to [[1.0]]
5042 
5043 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5044  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5045  A - matrix, array[N,N]
5046  IsUpper - (optional) storage type:
5047  * if True, symmetric matrix A is given by its upper
5048  triangle, and the lower triangle isn't used
5049  * if False, symmetric matrix A is given by its lower
5050  triangle, and the upper triangle isn't used
5051  * if not given, both lower and upper triangles must be
5052  filled.
5053 
5054  -- ALGLIB --
5055  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5056 *************************************************************************/
5057 void minqpsetquadratictermsparse(const minqpstate &state, const sparsematrix &a, const bool isupper, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5058

5061 This function sets starting point for QP solver. It is useful to have
5062 good initial approximation to the solution, because it will increase
5063 speed of convergence and identification of active constraints.
5064 
5065 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5066  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5067  X - starting point, array[N].
5068 
5069  -- ALGLIB --
5070  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey

5072 void minqpsetstartingpoint(const minqpstate &state, const real_1d_array &x, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5075 /*************************************************************************
5076 This function sets origin for QP solver. By default, following QP program
5077 is solved:
5078 
5079  min(0.5*x'*A*x+b'*x)
5080 
5081 This function allows to solve different problem:
5082 
5083  min(0.5*(x-x_origin)'*A*(x-x_origin)+b'*(x-x_origin))
5084 
5085 Specification of non-zero origin affects function being minimized, but not
5086 constraints. Box and linear constraints are still calculated without
5087 origin.
5088 
5089 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5090  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5091  XOrigin - origin, array[N].
5092 
5093  -- ALGLIB --
5094  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey

5096 void minqpsetorigin(const minqpstate &state, const real_1d_array &xorigin, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
