5098 
5099 /*************************************************************************
5100 This function sets scaling coefficients.
5101 
5102 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
5103 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances) and as
5104 preconditioner.
5105 
5106 Scale of the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
5107 a) "how large" the variable is
5108 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the
5109  function
5110 
5111 If you do not know how to choose scales of your variables, you can:
5112 * read www.alglib.net/optimization/scaling.php article
5113 * use minqpsetscaleautodiag(), which calculates scale using diagonal of
5114  the quadratic term: S is set to 1/sqrt(diag(A)), which works well
5115  sometimes.
5116 
5117 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5118  State - structure stores algorithm state
5119  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
5120  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
5121 
5122  -- ALGLIB --
5123  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5124 *************************************************************************/
5125 void minqpsetscale(const minqpstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5126 
5127 
5128 /*************************************************************************
5129 This function sets automatic evaluation of variable scaling.
5130 
5131 IMPORTANT: this function works only for matrices with positive diagonal
5132  elements! Zero or negative elements will result in -9 error
5133  code being returned. Specify scale vector manually with
5134  minqpsetscale() in such cases.
5135 
5136 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
5137 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances) and as
5138 preconditioner.
5139 
5140 The best way to set scaling is to manually specify variable scales.
5141 However, sometimes you just need quick-and-dirty solution - either when
5142 you perform fast prototyping, or when you know your problem well and you
5143 are 100% sure that this quick solution is robust enough in your case.
5144 
5145 One such solution is to evaluate scale of I-th variable as 1/Sqrt(A[i,i]),
5146 where A[i,i] is an I-th diagonal element of the quadratic term.
5147 
5148 Such approach works well sometimes, but you have to be careful here.
5149 
5150 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5151  State - structure stores algorithm state
5152 
5153  -- ALGLIB --
5154  Copyright 26.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
5155 *************************************************************************/
5156 void minqpsetscaleautodiag(const minqpstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5157 
5158 
5159 /*************************************************************************
5160 This function tells solver to use BLEIC-based algorithm and sets stopping
5161 criteria for the algorithm.
5162 
5163 This algorithm is fast enough for large-scale problems with following
5164 properties:
5165 a) feasible initial point, moderate amount of general linear constraints
5166 b) arbitrary (can be infeasible) initial point, small amount of general
5167  linear constraints (say, hundred or less)
5168 
5169 If you solve large-scale QP problem with many inequality constraints and
5170 without initial feasibility guarantees, consider using DENSE-AUL solver
5171 instead. Initial feasibility detection stage by BLEIC may take too long on
5172 such problems.
5173 
5174 ALGORITHM FEATURES:
5175 
5176 * supports dense and sparse QP problems
5177 * supports box and general linear equality/inequality constraints
5178 * can solve all types of problems (convex, semidefinite, nonconvex) as
5179  long as they are bounded from below under constraints.
5180  Say, it is possible to solve "min{-x^2} subject to -1<=x<=+1".
5181  Of course, global minimum is found only for positive definite and
5182  semidefinite problems. As for indefinite ones - only local minimum is
5183  found.
5184 
5185 ALGORITHM OUTLINE:
5186 
5187 * BLEIC-QP solver is just a driver function for MinBLEIC solver; it solves
5188  quadratic programming problem as general linearly constrained
5189  optimization problem, which is solved by means of BLEIC solver (part of
5190  ALGLIB, active set method).
5191 
5192 ALGORITHM LIMITATIONS:
5193 * This algorithm is inefficient on problems with hundreds and thousands
5194  of general inequality constraints and infeasible initial point. Initial
5195  feasibility detection stage may take too long on such constraint sets.
5196  Consider using DENSE-AUL instead.
5197 * unlike QuickQP solver, this algorithm does not perform Newton steps and
5198  does not use Level 3 BLAS. Being general-purpose active set method, it
5199  can activate constraints only one-by-one. Thus, its performance is lower
5200  than that of QuickQP.
5201 * its precision is also a bit inferior to that of QuickQP. BLEIC-QP
5202  performs only LBFGS steps (no Newton steps), which are good at detecting
5203  neighborhood of the solution, buy needs many iterations to find solution
5204  with more than 6 digits of precision.
5205 
5206 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5207  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5208  EpsG - >=0
5209  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
5210  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
5211  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5212  * v - scaled constrained gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
5213  * g - gradient
5214  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
5215  EpsF - >=0
5216  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
5217  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
5218  condition: |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
5219  EpsX - >=0
5220  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
5221  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
5222  condition:
5223  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5224  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
5225  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
5226  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
5227  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
5228  iterations is unlimited. NOTE: this algorithm uses LBFGS
5229  iterations, which are relatively cheap, but improve
5230  function value only a bit. So you will need many iterations
5231  to converge - from 0.1*N to 10*N, depending on problem's
5232  condition number.
5233 
5234 IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO CALL MinQPSetScale() WHEN YOU USE THIS ALGORITHM
5235 BECAUSE ITS STOPPING CRITERIA ARE SCALE-DEPENDENT!
5236 
5237 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
5238 to automatic stopping criterion selection (presently it is small step
5239 length, but it may change in the future versions of ALGLIB).
5240 
5241  -- ALGLIB --
5242  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5243 *************************************************************************/
5244 void minqpsetalgobleic(const minqpstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5245 
5246 
5247 /*************************************************************************
5248 This function tells QP solver to use Dense-AUL algorithm and sets stopping
5249 criteria for the algorithm.
5250 
5251 ALGORITHM FEATURES:
5252 
5253 * supports box and dense/sparse general linear equality/inequality
5254  constraints
5255 * convergence is theoretically proved for positive-definite (convex) QP
5256  problems. Semidefinite and non-convex problems can be solved as long as
5257  they are bounded from below under constraints, although without
5258  theoretical guarantees.
5259 * this solver is better than QP-BLEIC on problems with large number of
5260  general linear constraints. It better handles infeasible initial points.
5261 
5262 ALGORITHM OUTLINE:
5263 
5264 * this algorithm is an augmented Lagrangian method with dense
5265  preconditioner (hence its name). It is similar to barrier/penalty
5266  methods, but much more precise and faster.
5267 * it performs several outer iterations in order to refine values of the
5268  Lagrange multipliers. Single outer iteration is a solution of some
5269  unconstrained optimization problem: first it performs dense Cholesky
5270  factorization of the Hessian in order to build preconditioner (adaptive
5271  regularization is applied to enforce positive definiteness), and then
5272  it uses L-BFGS optimizer to solve optimization problem.
5273 * typically you need about 5-10 outer iterations to converge to solution
5274 
5275 ALGORITHM LIMITATIONS:
5276 
5277 * because dense Cholesky driver is used, this algorithm has O(N^2) memory
5278  requirements and O(OuterIterations*N^3) minimum running time. From the
5279  practical point of view, it limits its applicability by several
5280  thousands of variables.
5281  From the other side, variables count is the most limiting factor,
5282  and dependence on constraint count is much more lower. Assuming that
5283  constraint matrix is sparse, it may handle tens of thousands of general
5284  linear constraints.
5285 
5286 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5287  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5288  EpsX - >=0, stopping criteria for inner optimizer.
5289  Inner iterations are stopped when step length (with
5290  variable scaling being applied) is less than EpsX.
5291  See minqpsetscale() for more information on variable
5292  scaling.
5293  Rho - penalty coefficient, Rho>0:
5294  * large enough that algorithm converges with desired
5295  precision.
5296  * not TOO large to prevent ill-conditioning
5297  * recommended values are 100, 1000 or 10000
5298  ItsCnt - number of outer iterations:
5299  * recommended values: 10-15 (although in most cases it
5300  converges within 5 iterations, you may need a few more
5301  to be sure).
5302  * ItsCnt=0 means that small number of outer iterations is
5303  automatically chosen (10 iterations in current version).
5304  * ItsCnt=1 means that AUL algorithm performs just as usual
5305  penalty method.
5306  * ItsCnt>1 means that AUL algorithm performs specified
5307  number of outer iterations
5308 
5309 IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO CALL minqpsetscale() WHEN YOU USE THIS ALGORITHM
5310 BECAUSE ITS CONVERGENCE PROPERTIES AND STOPPING CRITERIA ARE SCALE-DEPENDENT!
5311 
5312 NOTE: Passing EpsX=0 will lead to automatic step length selection
5313  (specific step length chosen may change in the future versions of
5314  ALGLIB, so it is better to specify step length explicitly).
5315 
5316  -- ALGLIB --
5317  Copyright 20.08.2016 by Bochkanov Sergey
5318 *************************************************************************/
5319 void minqpsetalgodenseaul(const minqpstate &state, const double epsx, const double rho, const ae_int_t itscnt, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5320 
5321 
5322 /*************************************************************************
5323 This function tells solver to use QuickQP algorithm: special extra-fast
5324 algorithm for problems with box-only constrants. It may solve non-convex
5325 problems as long as they are bounded from below under constraints.
5326 
5327 ALGORITHM FEATURES:
5328 * many times (from 5x to 50x!) faster than BLEIC-based QP solver; utilizes
5329  accelerated methods for activation of constraints.
5330 * supports dense and sparse QP problems
5331 * supports ONLY box constraints; general linear constraints are NOT
5332  supported by this solver
5333 * can solve all types of problems (convex, semidefinite, nonconvex) as
5334  long as they are bounded from below under constraints.
5335  Say, it is possible to solve "min{-x^2} subject to -1<=x<=+1".
5336  In convex/semidefinite case global minimum is returned, in nonconvex
5337  case - algorithm returns one of the local minimums.
5338 
5339 ALGORITHM OUTLINE:
5340 
5341 * algorithm performs two kinds of iterations: constrained CG iterations
5342  and constrained Newton iterations
5343 * initially it performs small number of constrained CG iterations, which
5344  can efficiently activate/deactivate multiple constraints
5345 * after CG phase algorithm tries to calculate Cholesky decomposition and
5346  to perform several constrained Newton steps. If Cholesky decomposition
5347  failed (matrix is indefinite even under constraints), we perform more
5348  CG iterations until we converge to such set of constraints that system
5349  matrix becomes positive definite. Constrained Newton steps greatly
5350  increase convergence speed and precision.
5351 * algorithm interleaves CG and Newton iterations which allows to handle
5352  indefinite matrices (CG phase) and quickly converge after final set of
5353  constraints is found (Newton phase). Combination of CG and Newton phases
5354  is called "outer iteration".
5355 * it is possible to turn off Newton phase (beneficial for semidefinite
5356  problems - Cholesky decomposition will fail too often)
5357 
5358 ALGORITHM LIMITATIONS:
5359 
5360 * algorithm does not support general linear constraints; only box ones
5361  are supported
5362 * Cholesky decomposition for sparse problems is performed with Skyline
5363  Cholesky solver, which is intended for low-profile matrices. No profile-
5364  reducing reordering of variables is performed in this version of ALGLIB.
5365 * problems with near-zero negative eigenvalues (or exacty zero ones) may
5366  experience about 2-3x performance penalty. The reason is that Cholesky
5367  decomposition can not be performed until we identify directions of zero
5368  and negative curvature and activate corresponding boundary constraints -
5369  but we need a lot of trial and errors because these directions are hard
5370  to notice in the matrix spectrum.
5371  In this case you may turn off Newton phase of algorithm.
5372  Large negative eigenvalues are not an issue, so highly non-convex
5373  problems can be solved very efficiently.
5374 
5375 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5376  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5377  EpsG - >=0
5378  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
5379  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
5380  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5381  * v - scaled constrained gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
5382  * g - gradient
5383  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
5384  EpsF - >=0
5385  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
5386  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
5387  condition: |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
5388  EpsX - >=0
5389  The subroutine finishes its work if exploratory steepest
5390  descent step on k+1-th iteration satisfies following
5391  condition:
5392  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5393  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
5394  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
5395  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinQPSetScale()
5396  MaxOuterIts-maximum number of OUTER iterations. One outer iteration
5397  includes some amount of CG iterations (from 5 to ~N) and
5398  one or several (usually small amount) Newton steps. Thus,
5399  one outer iteration has high cost, but can greatly reduce
5400  funcation value.
5401  Use 0 if you do not want to limit number of outer iterations.
5402  UseNewton- use Newton phase or not:
5403  * Newton phase improves performance of positive definite
5404  dense problems (about 2 times improvement can be observed)
5405  * can result in some performance penalty on semidefinite
5406  or slightly negative definite problems - each Newton
5407  phase will bring no improvement (Cholesky failure), but
5408  still will require computational time.
5409  * if you doubt, you can turn off this phase - optimizer
5410  will retain its most of its high speed.
5411 
5412 IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO CALL MinQPSetScale() WHEN YOU USE THIS ALGORITHM
5413 BECAUSE ITS STOPPING CRITERIA ARE SCALE-DEPENDENT!
5414 
5415 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
5416 to automatic stopping criterion selection (presently it is small step
5417 length, but it may change in the future versions of ALGLIB).
5418 
5419  -- ALGLIB --
5420  Copyright 22.05.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
5421 *************************************************************************/
5422 void minqpsetalgoquickqp(const minqpstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxouterits, const bool usenewton, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5423 
5424 
5425 /*************************************************************************
5426 This function sets box constraints for QP solver
5427 
5428 Box constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation). After
5429 being set, they are preserved until explicitly turned off with another
5430 SetBC() call.
5431 
5432 All QP solvers may handle box constraints.
5433 
5434 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5435  State - structure stores algorithm state
5436  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
5437  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
5438  very small number or -INF (latter is recommended because
5439  it will allow solver to use better algorithm).
5440  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
5441  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
5442  very large number or +INF (latter is recommended because
5443  it will allow solver to use better algorithm).
5444 
5445 NOTE: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
5446 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
5447 
5448  -- ALGLIB --
5449  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5450 *************************************************************************/
5451 void minqpsetbc(const minqpstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5454 /*************************************************************************
5455 This function sets dense linear constraints for QP optimizer.
5456 
5457 This function overrides results of previous calls to minqpsetlc(),
5458 minqpsetlcsparse() and minqpsetlcmixed(). After call to this function
5459 sparse constraints are dropped, and you have only those constraints which
5460 were specified in the present call.
5461 
5462 If you want to specify mixed (with dense and sparse terms) linear
5463 constraints, you should call minqpsetlcmixed().
5464 
5465 SUPPORT BY QP SOLVERS:
5466 
5467 Following QP solvers can handle dense linear constraints:
5468 * BLEIC-QP - handles them with high precision, but may be
5469  inefficient for problems with hundreds of constraints
5470 * Dense-AUL-QP - handles them with moderate precision (approx. 10^-6),
5471  may efficiently handle thousands of constraints.
5472 
5473 Following QP solvers can NOT handle dense linear constraints:
5474 * QuickQP - can not handle general linear constraints
5475 
5476 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5477  State - structure previously allocated with MinQPCreate call.
5478  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
5479  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
5480  or inequality (see below):
5481  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
5482  * last element corresponds to the right part.
5483  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
5484  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
5485  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
5486  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
5487  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
5488  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
5489  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
5490  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
5491 
5492 NOTE 1: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately -
5493  there always exists some violation due to numerical errors and
5494  algorithmic limitations (BLEIC-QP solver is most precise, AUL-QP
5495  solver is less precise).
5496 
5497  -- ALGLIB --
5498  Copyright 19.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
5499 *************************************************************************/
5500 void minqpsetlc(const minqpstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5501 void minqpsetlc(const minqpstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5502 
5503 
5504 /*************************************************************************
5505 This function sets sparse linear constraints for QP optimizer.
5506 
5507 This function overrides results of previous calls to minqpsetlc(),
5508 minqpsetlcsparse() and minqpsetlcmixed(). After call to this function
5509 dense constraints are dropped, and you have only those constraints which
5510 were specified in the present call.
5511 
5512 If you want to specify mixed (with dense and sparse terms) linear
5513 constraints, you should call minqpsetlcmixed().
5514 
5515 SUPPORT BY QP SOLVERS:
5516 
5517 Following QP solvers can handle sparse linear constraints:
5518 * BLEIC-QP - handles them with high precision, but can not
5519  utilize their sparsity - sparse constraint matrix
5520  is silently converted to dense format. Thus, it
5521  may be inefficient for problems with hundreds of
5522  constraints.
5523 * Dense-AUL-QP - although this solver uses dense linear algebra to
5524  calculate Cholesky preconditioner, it may
5525  efficiently handle sparse constraints. It may
5526  solve problems with hundreds and thousands of
5527  constraints. The only drawback is that precision
5528  of constraint handling is typically within 1E-4...
5529  ..1E-6 range.
5530 
5531 Following QP solvers can NOT handle sparse linear constraints:
5532 * QuickQP - can not handle general linear constraints
5533 
5534 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5535  State - structure previously allocated with MinQPCreate call.
5536  C - linear constraints, sparse matrix with dimensions at
5537  least [K,N+1]. If matrix has larger size, only leading
5538  Kx(N+1) rectangle is used.
5539  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
5540  or inequality (see below):
5541  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
5542  * last element corresponds to the right part.
5543  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
5544  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
5545  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
5546  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
5547  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
5548  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0
5549 
5550 NOTE 1: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately -
5551  there always exists some violation due to numerical errors and
5552  algorithmic limitations (BLEIC-QP solver is most precise, AUL-QP
5553  solver is less precise).
5554 
5555  -- ALGLIB --
5556  Copyright 22.08.2016 by Bochkanov Sergey
5557 *************************************************************************/
5558 void minqpsetlcsparse(const minqpstate &state, const sparsematrix &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5560 
5561 /*************************************************************************
5562 This function sets mixed linear constraints, which include a set of dense
5563 rows, and a set of sparse rows.
5564 
5565 This function overrides results of previous calls to minqpsetlc(),
5566 minqpsetlcsparse() and minqpsetlcmixed().
5567 
5568 This function may be useful if constraint matrix includes large number of
5569 both types of rows - dense and sparse. If you have just a few sparse rows,
5570 you may represent them in dense format without loosing performance.
5571 Similarly, if you have just a few dense rows, you may store them in sparse
5572 format with almost same performance.
5573 
5574 SUPPORT BY QP SOLVERS:
5575 
5576 Following QP solvers can handle mixed dense/sparse linear constraints:
5577 * BLEIC-QP - handles them with high precision, but can not
5578  utilize their sparsity - sparse constraint matrix
5579  is silently converted to dense format. Thus, it
5580  may be inefficient for problems with hundreds of
5581  constraints.
5582 * Dense-AUL-QP - although this solver uses dense linear algebra to
5583  calculate Cholesky preconditioner, it may
5584  efficiently handle sparse constraints. It may
5585  solve problems with hundreds and thousands of
5586  constraints. The only drawback is that precision
5587  of constraint handling is typically within 1E-4...
5588  ..1E-6 range.
5589 
5590 Following QP solvers can NOT handle mixed linear constraints:
5591 * QuickQP - can not handle general linear constraints at all
5592 
5593 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5594  State - structure previously allocated with MinQPCreate call.
5595  DenseC - dense linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
5596  Each row of DenseC represents one constraint, either equality
5597  or inequality (see below):
5598  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
5599  * last element corresponds to the right part.
5600  All elements of DenseC (including right part) must be finite.
5601  DenseCT - type of constraints, array[K]:
5602  * if DenseCT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is DenseC[i,*]*x >= DenseC[i,n+1]
5603  * if DenseCT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is DenseC[i,*]*x = DenseC[i,n+1]
5604  * if DenseCT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is DenseC[i,*]*x <= DenseC[i,n+1]
5605  DenseK - number of equality/inequality constraints, DenseK>=0
5606  SparseC - linear constraints, sparse matrix with dimensions at
5607  least [SparseK,N+1]. If matrix has larger size, only leading
5608  SPARSEKx(N+1) rectangle is used.
5609  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
5610  or inequality (see below):
5611  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
5612  * last element corresponds to the right part.
5613  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
5614  SparseCT- type of sparse constraints, array[K]:
5615  * if SparseCT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is SparseC[i,*]*x >= SparseC[i,n+1]
5616  * if SparseCT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is SparseC[i,*]*x = SparseC[i,n+1]
5617  * if SparseCT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is SparseC[i,*]*x <= SparseC[i,n+1]
5618  SparseK - number of sparse equality/inequality constraints, K>=0
5619 
5620 NOTE 1: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately -
5621  there always exists some violation due to numerical errors and
5622  algorithmic limitations (BLEIC-QP solver is most precise, AUL-QP
5623  solver is less precise).
5624 
5625  -- ALGLIB --
5626  Copyright 22.08.2016 by Bochkanov Sergey
5627 *************************************************************************/
5628 void minqpsetlcmixed(const minqpstate &state, const real_2d_array &densec, const integer_1d_array &densect, const ae_int_t densek, const sparsematrix &sparsec, const integer_1d_array &sparsect, const ae_int_t sparsek, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5632 This function solves quadratic programming problem.
5633

5635 the following functions:
5636

5638 * minqpsetalgobleic() - for BLEIC-QP solver
5639 * minqpsetalgodenseaul() - for Dense-AUL-QP solver
5640 
5641 These functions also allow you to control stopping criteria of the solver.
5642 If you did not set solver, MinQP subpackage will automatically select
5643 solver for your problem and will run it with default stopping criteria.
5644 
5645 However, it is better to set explicitly solver and its stopping criteria.
5646

5649

5651 to this function.

5661 /*************************************************************************
5662 QP solver results
5663 
5664 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5665  State - algorithm state
5666 
5667 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5668  X - array[0..N-1], solution.
5669  This array is allocated and initialized only when
5670  Rep.TerminationType parameter is positive (success).
5671  Rep - optimization report. You should check Rep.TerminationType,
5672  which contains completion code, and you may check another
5673  fields which contain another information about algorithm
5674  functioning.
5675 
5676  Failure codes returned by algorithm are:
5677  * -9 failure of the automatic scale evaluation: one of
5678  the diagonal elements of the quadratic term is
5679  non-positive. Specify variable scales manually!
5680  * -5 inappropriate solver was used:
5681  * QuickQP solver for problem with general linear
5682  constraints
5683  * -4 BLEIC-QP/QuickQP solver found unconstrained
5684  direction of negative curvature (function is
5685  unbounded from below even under constraints), no
5686  meaningful minimum can be found.
5687  * -3 inconsistent constraints (or maybe feasible point
5688  is too hard to find). If you are sure that
5689  constraints are feasible, try to restart optimizer
5690  with better initial approximation.
5691 
5692  Completion codes specific for Cholesky algorithm:
5693  * 4 successful completion
5694 
5695  Completion codes specific for BLEIC/QuickQP algorithms:
5696  * 1 relative function improvement is no more than EpsF.
5697  * 2 scaled step is no more than EpsX.
5698  * 4 scaled gradient norm is no more than EpsG.
5699  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken
5700 
5701  -- ALGLIB --
5702  Copyright 11.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5703 *************************************************************************/
5704 void minqpresults(const minqpstate &state, real_1d_array &x, minqpreport &rep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5719 #endif
5720 
5721 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINBC) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5722 /*************************************************************************
5723  BOX CONSTRAINED OPTIMIZATION
5724  WITH FAST ACTIVATION OF MULTIPLE BOX CONSTRAINTS
5725 
5726 DESCRIPTION:
5727 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments subject to box
5728 constraints (with some of box constraints actually being equality ones).
5729 
5730 This optimizer uses algorithm similar to that of MinBLEIC (optimizer with
5731 general linear constraints), but presence of box-only constraints allows
5732 us to use faster constraint activation strategies. On large-scale problems,
5733 with multiple constraints active at the solution, this optimizer can be
5734 several times faster than BLEIC.
5735 
5736 REQUIREMENTS:
5737 * user must provide function value and gradient
5738 * starting point X0 must be feasible or
5739  not too far away from the feasible set
5740 * grad(f) must be Lipschitz continuous on a level set:
5741  L = { x : f(x)<=f(x0) }
5742 * function must be defined everywhere on the feasible set F
5743 
5744 USAGE:
5745 
5746 Constrained optimization if far more complex than the unconstrained one.
5747 Here we give very brief outline of the BC optimizer. We strongly recommend
5748 you to read examples in the ALGLIB Reference Manual and to read ALGLIB User Guide
5749 on optimization, which is available at http://www.alglib.net/optimization/
5750 
5751 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinBCCreate() call
5752 
5753 2. USer adds box constraints by calling MinBCSetBC() function.
5754 
5755 3. User sets stopping conditions with MinBCSetCond().
5756 
5757 4. User calls MinBCOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
5758  pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates F/G.
5759 
5760 5. User calls MinBCResults() to get solution
5761 
5762 6. Optionally user may call MinBCRestartFrom() to solve another problem
5763  with same N but another starting point.
5764  MinBCRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
5765 
5766 
5767 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5768  N - problem dimension, N>0:
5769  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
5770  * if not given, automatically determined from size ofX
5771  X - starting point, array[N]:
5772  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
5773  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
5774  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
5775  approximation.
5776 
5777 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5778  State - structure stores algorithm state
5779 
5780  -- ALGLIB --
5781  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5782 *************************************************************************/
5783 void minbccreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5784 void minbccreate(const real_1d_array &x, minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5785 
5786 
5787 /*************************************************************************
5788 The subroutine is finite difference variant of MinBCCreate(). It uses
5789 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
5790 
5791 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
5792 only. We recommend to read comments on MinBCCreate() in order to get
5793 more information about creation of BC optimizer.
5794 
5795 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5796  N - problem dimension, N>0:
5797  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
5798  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
5799  X - starting point, array[0..N-1].
5800  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
5801 
5802 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5803  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5804 
5805 NOTES:
5806 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
5807 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
5808  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinBCSetScale() call.
5809 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
5810  large step will result in too large truncation errors, while too small
5811  step will result in too large numerical errors. 1.0E-6 can be good
5812  value to start with.
5813 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
5814  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
5815  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
5816  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
5817  small ones.
5818  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
5819  is less robust and precise. CG needs exact gradient values. Imprecise
5820  gradient may slow down convergence, especially on highly nonlinear
5821  problems.
5822  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
5823  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
5824  as possible.
5825 
5826  -- ALGLIB --
5827  Copyright 16.05.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5828 *************************************************************************/
5829 void minbccreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5830 void minbccreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5831 
5832 
5833 /*************************************************************************
5834 This function sets boundary constraints for BC optimizer.
5835 
5836 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
5837 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinBCRestartFrom().
5838 
5839 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5840  State - structure stores algorithm state
5841  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
5842  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
5843  very small number or -INF.
5844  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
5845  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
5846  very large number or +INF.
5847 
5848 NOTE 1: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
5849 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
5850 
5851 NOTE 2: this solver has following useful properties:
5852 * bound constraints are always satisfied exactly
5853 * function is evaluated only INSIDE area specified by bound constraints,
5854  even when numerical differentiation is used (algorithm adjusts nodes
5855  according to boundary constraints)
5856 
5857  -- ALGLIB --
5858  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5859 *************************************************************************/
5860 void minbcsetbc(const minbcstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5861 
5862 
5863 /*************************************************************************
5864 This function sets stopping conditions for the optimizer.
5865 
5866 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5867  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5868  EpsG - >=0
5869  The subroutine finishes its work if the condition
5870  |v|<EpsG is satisfied, where:
5871  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5872  * v - scaled gradient vector, v[i]=g[i]*s[i]
5873  * g - gradient
5874  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBCSetScale()
5875  EpsF - >=0
5876  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
5877  the condition |F(k+1)-F(k)|<=EpsF*max{|F(k)|,|F(k+1)|,1}
5878  is satisfied.
5879  EpsX - >=0
5880  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
5881  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
5882  * |.| means Euclidian norm
5883  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
5884  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
5885  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinBCSetScale()
5886  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
5887  iterations is unlimited.
5888 
5889 Passing EpsG=0, EpsF=0 and EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead
5890 to automatic stopping criterion selection.
5891 
5892 NOTE: when SetCond() called with non-zero MaxIts, BC solver may perform
5893  slightly more than MaxIts iterations. I.e., MaxIts sets non-strict
5894  limit on iterations count.
5895 
5896  -- ALGLIB --
5897  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5898 *************************************************************************/
5899 void minbcsetcond(const minbcstate &state, const double epsg, const double epsf, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5900 
5901 
5902 /*************************************************************************
5903 This function sets scaling coefficients for BC optimizer.
5904 
5905 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
5906 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
5907 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
5908 a) "how large" the variable is
5909 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
5910 
5911 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
5912 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
5913 
5914 In most optimizers (and in the BC too) scaling is NOT a form of
5915 preconditioning. It just affects stopping conditions. You should set
5916 preconditioner by separate call to one of the MinBCSetPrec...()
5917 functions.
5918 
5919 There is a special preconditioning mode, however, which uses scaling
5920 coefficients to form diagonal preconditioning matrix. You can turn this
5921 mode on, if you want. But you should understand that scaling is not the
5922 same thing as preconditioning - these are two different, although related
5923 forms of tuning solver.
5924 
5925 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5926  State - structure stores algorithm state
5927  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
5928  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
5929 
5930  -- ALGLIB --
5931  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5932 *************************************************************************/
5933 void minbcsetscale(const minbcstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5934

5967 /*************************************************************************
5968 Modification of the preconditioner: scale-based diagonal preconditioning.
5969 
5970 This preconditioning mode can be useful when you don't have approximate
5971 diagonal of Hessian, but you know that your variables are badly scaled
5972 (for example, one variable is in [1,10], and another in [1000,100000]),
5973 and most part of the ill-conditioning comes from different scales of vars.
5974 
5975 In this case simple scale-based preconditioner, with H[i] = 1/(s[i]^2),
5976 can greatly improve convergence.
5977 
5978 IMPRTANT: you should set scale of your variables with MinBCSetScale()
5979 call (before or after MinBCSetPrecScale() call). Without knowledge of
5980 the scale of your variables scale-based preconditioner will be just unit
5981 matrix.
5982 
5983 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5984  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5985 
5986  -- ALGLIB --
5987  Copyright 13.10.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
5988 *************************************************************************/
5989 void minbcsetprecscale(const minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6036 /*************************************************************************
6037 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
6038 
6039 These functions accept following parameters:
6040  state - algorithm state
6041  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
6042  value func at given point x
6043  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
6044  value func and gradient grad at given point x
6045  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
6046  can be NULL
6047  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
6048  can be NULL
6049 
6050 NOTES:
6051 
6052 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
6053  (analytical) user-supplied gradient, and one which uses function value
6054  only and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
6055  gradient.
6056 
6057  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
6058  (either MinBCCreate() for analytical gradient or MinBCCreateF()
6059  for numerical differentiation) you should choose appropriate variant of
6060  MinBCOptimize() - one which accepts function AND gradient or one
6061  which accepts function ONLY.
6062 
6063  Be careful to choose variant of MinBCOptimize() which corresponds to
6064  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
6065  callback (function/gradient) passed to MinBCOptimize() and specific
6066  function used to create optimizer.
6067 
6068 
6069  | USER PASSED TO MinBCOptimize()
6070  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
6071  ------------------------------------------------------------
6072  MinBCCreateF() | works FAILS
6073  MinBCCreate() | FAILS works
6074 
6075  Here "FAIL" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
6076  function and MinBCOptimize() version. Attemps to use such
6077  combination (for example, to create optimizer with MinBCCreateF()
6078  and to pass gradient information to MinCGOptimize()) will lead to
6079  exception being thrown. Either you did not pass gradient when it WAS
6080  needed or you passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
6081 
6082  -- ALGLIB --
6083  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
6084 
6085 *************************************************************************/
6086 void minbcoptimize(minbcstate &state,

6088  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,
6089  void *ptr = NULL,
6090  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6173 void minbcrestartfrom(const minbcstate &state, const real_1d_array &x, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6176 /*************************************************************************
6177 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
6178 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
6179 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
6180 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
6181 submitted and returns error code 8 (successful termination).
6182 
6183 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6184  State - optimizer structure
6185 
6186 NOTE: after request for termination optimizer may perform several
6187  additional calls to user-supplied callbacks. It does NOT guarantee
6188  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
6189  will be discarded later.
6190 
6191 NOTE: calling this function on optimizer which is NOT running will have no
6192  effect.
6193 
6194 NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
6195  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
6196 
6197  -- ALGLIB --
6198  Copyright 08.10.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6199 *************************************************************************/
6200 void minbcrequesttermination(const minbcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6202 
6203 /*************************************************************************
6204 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
6205 gradient:
6206 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
6207 * MinBCOptimize() is called
6208 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
6209  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
6210  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
6211  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
6212  of i-th parameter
6213  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
6214  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
6215  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
6216  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
6217  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
6218  point
6219  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
6220  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
6221  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative.
6222 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
6223 
6224 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
6225  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
6226  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
6227  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
6228  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
6229  some third party).
6230 
6231 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
6232  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
6233  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
6234  parameters by means of setting scale with MinBCSetScale().
6235 
6236 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
6237  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
6238  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
6239  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
6240  function.
6241 
6242 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6243  State - structure used to store algorithm state
6244  TestStep - verification step:
6245  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
6246  * TestStep>0 activates verification
6247 
6248  -- ALGLIB --
6249  Copyright 15.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
6250 *************************************************************************/
6251 void minbcsetgradientcheck(const minbcstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6252 #endif
6253 
6254 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_NLCSLP) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
6255 
6256 #endif
6257 
6258 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINNLC) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
6259 /*************************************************************************
6260  NONLINEARLY CONSTRAINED OPTIMIZATION
6261  WITH PRECONDITIONED AUGMENTED LAGRANGIAN ALGORITHM
6262 
6263 DESCRIPTION:
6264 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments subject to any
6265 combination of:
6266 * bound constraints
6267 * linear inequality constraints
6268 * linear equality constraints
6269 * nonlinear equality constraints Gi(x)=0
6270 * nonlinear inequality constraints Hi(x)<=0
6271 
6272 REQUIREMENTS:
6273 * user must provide function value and gradient for F(), H(), G()
6274 * starting point X0 must be feasible or not too far away from the feasible
6275  set
6276 * F(), G(), H() are twice continuously differentiable on the feasible set
6277  and its neighborhood
6278 * nonlinear constraints G() and H() must have non-zero gradient at G(x)=0
6279  and at H(x)=0. Say, constraint like x^2>=1 is supported, but x^2>=0 is
6280  NOT supported.
6281 
6282 USAGE:
6283 
6284 Constrained optimization if far more complex than the unconstrained one.
6285 Nonlinearly constrained optimization is one of the most esoteric numerical
6286 procedures.
6287 
6288 Here we give very brief outline of the MinNLC optimizer. We strongly
6289 recommend you to study examples in the ALGLIB Reference Manual and to read
6290 ALGLIB User Guide on optimization, which is available at
6291 http://www.alglib.net/optimization/
6292 
6293 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinNLCCreate() call and chooses
6294  what NLC solver to use. There is some solver which is used by default,
6295  with default settings, but you should NOT rely on default choice. It
6296  may change in future releases of ALGLIB without notice, and no one can
6297  guarantee that new solver will be able to solve your problem with
6298  default settings.
6299 
6300  From the other side, if you choose solver explicitly, you can be pretty
6301  sure that it will work with new ALGLIB releases.
6302 
6303  In the current release following solvers can be used:
6304  * SLP solver (activated with MinNLCSetAlgoSLP() function) - successive
6305  linear programming, recommended option (default)
6306  * AUL solver (activated with MinNLCSetAlgoAUL() function) - augmented
6307  Lagrangian method with dense preconditioner
6308 
6309 2. User adds boundary and/or linear and/or nonlinear constraints by means
6310  of calling one of the following functions:
6311  a) MinNLCSetBC() for boundary constraints
6312  b) MinNLCSetLC() for linear constraints
6313  c) MinNLCSetNLC() for nonlinear constraints
6314  You may combine (a), (b) and (c) in one optimization problem.
6315 
6316 3. User sets scale of the variables with MinNLCSetScale() function. It is
6317  VERY important to set scale of the variables, because nonlinearly
6318  constrained problems are hard to solve when variables are badly scaled.
6319 
6320 4. User sets stopping conditions with MinNLCSetCond(). If NLC solver
6321  uses inner/outer iteration layout, this function sets stopping
6322  conditions for INNER iterations.
6323 
6324 5. Finally, user calls MinNLCOptimize() function which takes algorithm
6325  state and pointer (delegate, etc.) to callback function which calculates
6326  F/G/H.
6327 
6328 6. User calls MinNLCResults() to get solution
6329 
6330 7. Optionally user may call MinNLCRestartFrom() to solve another problem
6331  with same N but another starting point. MinNLCRestartFrom() allows to
6332  reuse already initialized structure.
6333 
6334 
6335 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6336  N - problem dimension, N>0:
6337  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
6338  * if not given, automatically determined from size ofX
6339  X - starting point, array[N]:
6340  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
6341  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
6342  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
6343  approximation.
6344 
6345 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
6346  State - structure stores algorithm state
6347 
6348  -- ALGLIB --
6349  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6350 *************************************************************************/
6351 void minnlccreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6352 void minnlccreate(const real_1d_array &x, minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6353 
6354 
6355 /*************************************************************************
6356 This subroutine is a finite difference variant of MinNLCCreate(). It uses
6357 finite differences in order to differentiate target function.
6358 
6359 Description below contains information which is specific to this function
6360 only. We recommend to read comments on MinNLCCreate() in order to get more
6361 information about creation of NLC optimizer.
6362 
6363 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6364  N - problem dimension, N>0:
6365  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
6366  * if not given, automatically determined from size ofX
6367  X - starting point, array[N]:
6368  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
6369  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
6370  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
6371  approximation.
6372  DiffStep- differentiation step, >0
6373 
6374 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
6375  State - structure stores algorithm state
6376 
6377 NOTES:
6378 1. algorithm uses 4-point central formula for differentiation.
6379 2. differentiation step along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I] where
6380  S[] is scaling vector which can be set by MinNLCSetScale() call.
6381 3. we recommend you to use moderate values of differentiation step. Too
6382  large step will result in too large TRUNCATION errors, while too small
6383  step will result in too large NUMERICAL errors. 1.0E-4 can be good
6384  value to start from.
6385 4. Numerical differentiation is very inefficient - one gradient
6386  calculation needs 4*N function evaluations. This function will work for
6387  any N - either small (1...10), moderate (10...100) or large (100...).
6388  However, performance penalty will be too severe for any N's except for
6389  small ones.
6390  We should also say that code which relies on numerical differentiation
6391  is less robust and precise. Imprecise gradient may slow down
6392  convergence, especially on highly nonlinear problems.
6393  Thus we recommend to use this function for fast prototyping on small-
6394  dimensional problems only, and to implement analytical gradient as soon
6395  as possible.
6396 
6397  -- ALGLIB --
6398  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6399 *************************************************************************/
6400 void minnlccreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6401 void minnlccreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6402 
6403 
6404 /*************************************************************************
6405 This function sets boundary constraints for NLC optimizer.
6406 
6407 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
6408 They are preserved after algorithm restart with MinNLCRestartFrom().
6409 
6410 You may combine boundary constraints with general linear ones - and with
6411 nonlinear ones! Boundary constraints are handled more efficiently than
6412 other types. Thus, if your problem has mixed constraints, you may
6413 explicitly specify some of them as boundary and save some time/space.
6414 
6415 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6416  State - structure stores algorithm state
6417  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
6418  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
6419  very small number or -INF.
6420  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
6421  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
6422  very large number or +INF.
6423 
6424 NOTE 1: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
6425 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
6426 
6427 NOTE 2: when you solve your problem with augmented Lagrangian solver,
6428  boundary constraints are satisfied only approximately! It is
6429  possible that algorithm will evaluate function outside of
6430  feasible area!
6431 
6432  -- ALGLIB --
6433  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6434 *************************************************************************/
6435 void minnlcsetbc(const minnlcstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6437 
6438 /*************************************************************************
6439 This function sets linear constraints for MinNLC optimizer.
6440 
6441 Linear constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation). They
6442 are preserved after algorithm restart with MinNLCRestartFrom().
6443 
6444 You may combine linear constraints with boundary ones - and with nonlinear
6445 ones! If your problem has mixed constraints, you may explicitly specify
6446 some of them as linear. It may help optimizer to handle them more
6447 efficiently.
6448 
6449 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6450  State - structure previously allocated with MinNLCCreate call.
6451  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
6452  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
6453  or inequality (see below):
6454  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
6455  * last element corresponds to the right part.
6456  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
6457  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
6458  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
6459  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
6460  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
6461  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
6462  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
6463  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
6464 
6465 NOTE 1: when you solve your problem with augmented Lagrangian solver,
6466  linear constraints are satisfied only approximately! It is
6467  possible that algorithm will evaluate function outside of
6468  feasible area!
6469 
6470  -- ALGLIB --
6471  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6472 *************************************************************************/
6473 void minnlcsetlc(const minnlcstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6474 void minnlcsetlc(const minnlcstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6476 
6477 /*************************************************************************
6478 This function sets nonlinear constraints for MinNLC optimizer.
6479 
6480 In fact, this function sets NUMBER of nonlinear constraints. Constraints
6481 itself (constraint functions) are passed to MinNLCOptimize() method. This
6482 method requires user-defined vector function F[] and its Jacobian J[],
6483 where:
6484 * first component of F[] and first row of Jacobian J[] corresponds to
6485  function being minimized
6486 * next NLEC components of F[] (and rows of J) correspond to nonlinear
6487  equality constraints G_i(x)=0
6488 * next NLIC components of F[] (and rows of J) correspond to nonlinear
6489  inequality constraints H_i(x)<=0
6490 
6491 NOTE: you may combine nonlinear constraints with linear/boundary ones. If
6492  your problem has mixed constraints, you may explicitly specify some
6493  of them as linear ones. It may help optimizer to handle them more
6494  efficiently.
6495 
6496 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6497  State - structure previously allocated with MinNLCCreate call.
6498  NLEC - number of Non-Linear Equality Constraints (NLEC), >=0
6499  NLIC - number of Non-Linear Inquality Constraints (NLIC), >=0
6500 
6501 NOTE 1: when you solve your problem with augmented Lagrangian solver,
6502  nonlinear constraints are satisfied only approximately! It is
6503  possible that algorithm will evaluate function outside of
6504  feasible area!
6505 
6506 NOTE 2: algorithm scales variables according to scale specified by
6507  MinNLCSetScale() function, so it can handle problems with badly
6508  scaled variables (as long as we KNOW their scales).
6509 
6510  However, there is no way to automatically scale nonlinear
6511  constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x). Inappropriate scaling of Gi/Hi may
6512  ruin convergence. Solving problem with constraint "1000*G0(x)=0"
6513  is NOT same as solving it with constraint "0.001*G0(x)=0".
6514 
6515  It means that YOU are the one who is responsible for correct
6516  scaling of nonlinear constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x). We recommend you
6517  to scale nonlinear constraints in such way that I-th component of
6518  dG/dX (or dH/dx) has approximately unit magnitude (for problems
6519  with unit scale) or has magnitude approximately equal to 1/S[i]
6520  (where S is a scale set by MinNLCSetScale() function).
6521 
6522 
6523  -- ALGLIB --
6524  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6525 *************************************************************************/
6526 void minnlcsetnlc(const minnlcstate &state, const ae_int_t nlec, const ae_int_t nlic, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6529 /*************************************************************************
6530 This function sets stopping conditions for inner iterations of optimizer.
6531 
6532 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6533  State - structure which stores algorithm state
6534  EpsX - >=0
6535  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
6536  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
6537  * |.| means Euclidian norm
6538  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
6539  * dx - step vector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
6540  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinNLCSetScale()
6541  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
6542  iterations is unlimited.
6543 
6544 Passing EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to automatic
6545 selection of the stopping condition.
6546 
6547  -- ALGLIB --
6548  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6549 *************************************************************************/
6550 void minnlcsetcond(const minnlcstate &state, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6552 
6553 /*************************************************************************
6554 This function sets scaling coefficients for NLC optimizer.
6555 
6556 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
6557 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
6558 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
6559 a) "how large" the variable is
6560 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
6561 
6562 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
6563 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
6564 
6565 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6566  State - structure stores algorithm state
6567  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
6568  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
6569 
6570  -- ALGLIB --
6571  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6572 *************************************************************************/
6573 void minnlcsetscale(const minnlcstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6575 
6576 /*************************************************************************
6577 This function sets preconditioner to "inexact LBFGS-based" mode.
6578 
6579 Preconditioning is very important for convergence of Augmented Lagrangian
6580 algorithm because presence of penalty term makes problem ill-conditioned.
6581 Difference between performance of preconditioned and unpreconditioned
6582 methods can be as large as 100x!
6583 
6584 MinNLC optimizer may use following preconditioners, each with its own
6585 benefits and drawbacks:
6586  a) inexact LBFGS-based, with O(N*K) evaluation time
6587  b) exact low rank one, with O(N*K^2) evaluation time
6588  c) exact robust one, with O(N^3+K*N^2) evaluation time
6589 where K is a total number of general linear and nonlinear constraints (box
6590 ones are not counted).
6591 
6592 Inexact LBFGS-based preconditioner uses L-BFGS formula combined with
6593 orthogonality assumption to perform very fast updates. For a N-dimensional
6594 problem with K general linear or nonlinear constraints (boundary ones are
6595 not counted) it has O(N*K) cost per iteration. This preconditioner has
6596 best quality (less iterations) when general linear and nonlinear
6597 constraints are orthogonal to each other (orthogonality with respect to
6598 boundary constraints is not required). Number of iterations increases when
6599 constraints are non-orthogonal, because algorithm assumes orthogonality,
6600 but still it is better than no preconditioner at all.
6601 
6602 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6603  State - structure stores algorithm state
6604 
6605  -- ALGLIB --
6606  Copyright 26.09.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6607 *************************************************************************/
6608 void minnlcsetprecinexact(const minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6609 
6610 
6611 /*************************************************************************
6612 This function sets preconditioner to "exact low rank" mode.
6613 
6614 Preconditioning is very important for convergence of Augmented Lagrangian
6615 algorithm because presence of penalty term makes problem ill-conditioned.
6616 Difference between performance of preconditioned and unpreconditioned
6617 methods can be as large as 100x!
6618 
6619 MinNLC optimizer may use following preconditioners, each with its own
6620 benefits and drawbacks:
6621  a) inexact LBFGS-based, with O(N*K) evaluation time
6622  b) exact low rank one, with O(N*K^2) evaluation time
6623  c) exact robust one, with O(N^3+K*N^2) evaluation time
6624 where K is a total number of general linear and nonlinear constraints (box
6625 ones are not counted).
6626 
6627 It also provides special unpreconditioned mode of operation which can be
6628 used for test purposes. Comments below discuss low rank preconditioner.
6629 
6630 Exact low-rank preconditioner uses Woodbury matrix identity to build
6631 quadratic model of the penalized function. It has following features:
6632 * no special assumptions about orthogonality of constraints
6633 * preconditioner evaluation is optimized for K<<N. Its cost is O(N*K^2),
6634  so it may become prohibitively slow for K>=N.
6635 * finally, stability of the process is guaranteed only for K<<N. Woodbury
6636  update often fail for K>=N due to degeneracy of intermediate matrices.
6637  That's why we recommend to use "exact robust" preconditioner for such
6638  cases.
6639 
6640 RECOMMENDATIONS
6641 
6642 We recommend to choose between "exact low rank" and "exact robust"
6643 preconditioners, with "low rank" version being chosen when you know in
6644 advance that total count of non-box constraints won't exceed N, and "robust"
6645 version being chosen when you need bulletproof solution.
6646 
6647 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6648  State - structure stores algorithm state
6649  UpdateFreq- update frequency. Preconditioner is rebuilt after every
6650  UpdateFreq iterations. Recommended value: 10 or higher.
6651  Zero value means that good default value will be used.
6652 
6653  -- ALGLIB --
6654  Copyright 26.09.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6655 *************************************************************************/
6656 void minnlcsetprecexactlowrank(const minnlcstate &state, const ae_int_t updatefreq, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6657 
6658 
6659 /*************************************************************************
6660 This function sets preconditioner to "exact robust" mode.
6661 
6662 Preconditioning is very important for convergence of Augmented Lagrangian
6663 algorithm because presence of penalty term makes problem ill-conditioned.
6664 Difference between performance of preconditioned and unpreconditioned
6665 methods can be as large as 100x!
6666 
6667 MinNLC optimizer may use following preconditioners, each with its own
6668 benefits and drawbacks:
6669  a) inexact LBFGS-based, with O(N*K) evaluation time
6670  b) exact low rank one, with O(N*K^2) evaluation time
6671  c) exact robust one, with O(N^3+K*N^2) evaluation time
6672 where K is a total number of general linear and nonlinear constraints (box
6673 ones are not counted).
6674 
6675 It also provides special unpreconditioned mode of operation which can be
6676 used for test purposes. Comments below discuss robust preconditioner.
6677 
6678 Exact robust preconditioner uses Cholesky decomposition to invert
6679 approximate Hessian matrix H=D+W'*C*W (where D stands for diagonal terms
6680 of Hessian, combined result of initial scaling matrix and penalty from box
6681 constraints; W stands for general linear constraints and linearization of
6682 nonlinear ones; C stands for diagonal matrix of penalty coefficients).
6683 
6684 This preconditioner has following features:
6685 * no special assumptions about constraint structure
6686 * preconditioner is optimized for stability; unlike "exact low rank"
6687  version which fails for K>=N, this one works well for any value of K.
6688 * the only drawback is that is takes O(N^3+K*N^2) time to build it. No
6689  economical Woodbury update is applied even when it makes sense, thus
6690  there are exist situations (K<<N) when "exact low rank" preconditioner
6691  outperforms this one.
6692 
6693 RECOMMENDATIONS
6694 
6695 We recommend to choose between "exact low rank" and "exact robust"
6696 preconditioners, with "low rank" version being chosen when you know in
6697 advance that total count of non-box constraints won't exceed N, and "robust"
6698 version being chosen when you need bulletproof solution.
6699 
6700 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6701  State - structure stores algorithm state
6702  UpdateFreq- update frequency. Preconditioner is rebuilt after every
6703  UpdateFreq iterations. Recommended value: 10 or higher.
6704  Zero value means that good default value will be used.
6705 
6706  -- ALGLIB --
6707  Copyright 26.09.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6708 *************************************************************************/
6709 void minnlcsetprecexactrobust(const minnlcstate &state, const ae_int_t updatefreq, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6710 
6711 
6712 /*************************************************************************
6713 This function sets preconditioner to "turned off" mode.
6714 
6715 Preconditioning is very important for convergence of Augmented Lagrangian
6716 algorithm because presence of penalty term makes problem ill-conditioned.
6717 Difference between performance of preconditioned and unpreconditioned
6718 methods can be as large as 100x!
6719 
6720 MinNLC optimizer may utilize two preconditioners, each with its own
6721 benefits and drawbacks: a) inexact LBFGS-based, and b) exact low rank one.
6722 It also provides special unpreconditioned mode of operation which can be
6723 used for test purposes.
6724 
6725 This function activates this test mode. Do not use it in production code
6726 to solve real-life problems.
6727 
6728 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6729  State - structure stores algorithm state

6734 void minnlcsetprecnone(const minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6737 /*************************************************************************
6738 This function sets maximum step length (after scaling of step vector with
6739 respect to variable scales specified by minnlcsetscale() call).
6740 
6741 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6742  State - structure which stores algorithm state
6743  StpMax - maximum step length, >=0. Set StpMax to 0.0 (default), if
6744  you don't want to limit step length.

6747 or other fast growing functions, and optimization algorithm makes too
6748 large steps which leads to overflow. This function allows us to reject
6749 steps that are too large (and therefore expose us to the possible
6750 overflow) without actually calculating function value at the x+stp*d.

6753  for step; AUL solver uses 2-norm, whilst SLP solver uses INF-norm.
