6760 
6761 /*************************************************************************
6762 This function tells MinNLC unit to use Augmented Lagrangian algorithm
6763 for nonlinearly constrained optimization. This algorithm is a slight
6764 modification of one described in "A Modified Barrier-Augmented Lagrangian
6765 Method for Constrained Minimization (1999)" by D.GOLDFARB, R.POLYAK,
6766 K. SCHEINBERG, I.YUZEFOVICH.
6767 
6768 Augmented Lagrangian algorithm works by converting problem of minimizing
6769 F(x) subject to equality/inequality constraints to unconstrained problem
6770 of the form
6771 
6772  min[ f(x) +
6773  + Rho*PENALTY_EQ(x) + SHIFT_EQ(x,Nu1) +
6774  + Rho*PENALTY_INEQ(x) + SHIFT_INEQ(x,Nu2) ]
6775 
6776 where:
6777 * Rho is a fixed penalization coefficient
6778 * PENALTY_EQ(x) is a penalty term, which is used to APPROXIMATELY enforce
6779  equality constraints
6780 * SHIFT_EQ(x) is a special "shift" term which is used to "fine-tune"
6781  equality constraints, greatly increasing precision
6782 * PENALTY_INEQ(x) is a penalty term which is used to approximately enforce
6783  inequality constraints
6784 * SHIFT_INEQ(x) is a special "shift" term which is used to "fine-tune"
6785  inequality constraints, greatly increasing precision
6786 * Nu1/Nu2 are vectors of Lagrange coefficients which are fine-tuned during
6787  outer iterations of algorithm
6788 
6789 This version of AUL algorithm uses preconditioner, which greatly
6790 accelerates convergence. Because this algorithm is similar to penalty
6791 methods, it may perform steps into infeasible area. All kinds of
6792 constraints (boundary, linear and nonlinear ones) may be violated in
6793 intermediate points - and in the solution. However, properly configured
6794 AUL method is significantly better at handling constraints than barrier
6795 and/or penalty methods.
6796 
6797 The very basic outline of algorithm is given below:
6798 1) first outer iteration is performed with "default" values of Lagrange
6799  multipliers Nu1/Nu2. Solution quality is low (candidate point can be
6800  too far away from true solution; large violation of constraints is
6801  possible) and is comparable with that of penalty methods.
6802 2) subsequent outer iterations refine Lagrange multipliers and improve
6803  quality of the solution.
6804 
6805 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6806  State - structure which stores algorithm state
6807  Rho - penalty coefficient, Rho>0:
6808  * large enough that algorithm converges with desired
6809  precision. Minimum value is 10*max(S'*diag(H)*S), where
6810  S is a scale matrix (set by MinNLCSetScale) and H is a
6811  Hessian of the function being minimized. If you can not
6812  easily estimate Hessian norm, see our recommendations
6813  below.
6814  * not TOO large to prevent ill-conditioning
6815  * for unit-scale problems (variables and Hessian have unit
6816  magnitude), Rho=100 or Rho=1000 can be used.
6817  * it is important to note that Rho is internally multiplied
6818  by scaling matrix, i.e. optimum value of Rho depends on
6819  scale of variables specified by MinNLCSetScale().
6820  ItsCnt - number of outer iterations:
6821  * ItsCnt=0 means that small number of outer iterations is
6822  automatically chosen (10 iterations in current version).
6823  * ItsCnt=1 means that AUL algorithm performs just as usual
6824  barrier method.
6825  * ItsCnt>1 means that AUL algorithm performs specified
6826  number of outer iterations
6827 
6828 HOW TO CHOOSE PARAMETERS
6829 
6830 Nonlinear optimization is a tricky area and Augmented Lagrangian algorithm
6831 is sometimes hard to tune. Good values of Rho and ItsCnt are problem-
6832 specific. In order to help you we prepared following set of
6833 recommendations:
6834 
6835 * for unit-scale problems (variables and Hessian have unit magnitude),
6836  Rho=100 or Rho=1000 can be used.
6837 
6838 * start from some small value of Rho and solve problem with just one
6839  outer iteration (ItcCnt=1). In this case algorithm behaves like penalty
6840  method. Increase Rho in 2x or 10x steps until you see that one outer
6841  iteration returns point which is "rough approximation to solution".
6842 
6843  It is very important to have Rho so large that penalty term becomes
6844  constraining i.e. modified function becomes highly convex in constrained
6845  directions.
6846 
6847  From the other side, too large Rho may prevent you from converging to
6848  the solution. You can diagnose it by studying number of inner iterations
6849  performed by algorithm: too few (5-10 on 1000-dimensional problem) or
6850  too many (orders of magnitude more than dimensionality) usually means
6851  that Rho is too large.
6852 
6853 * with just one outer iteration you usually have low-quality solution.
6854  Some constraints can be violated with very large margin, while other
6855  ones (which are NOT violated in the true solution) can push final point
6856  too far in the inner area of the feasible set.
6857 
6858  For example, if you have constraint x0>=0 and true solution x0=1, then
6859  merely a presence of "x0>=0" will introduce a bias towards larger values
6860  of x0. Say, algorithm may stop at x0=1.5 instead of 1.0.
6861 
6862 * after you found good Rho, you may increase number of outer iterations.
6863  ItsCnt=10 is a good value. Subsequent outer iteration will refine values
6864  of Lagrange multipliers. Constraints which were violated will be
6865  enforced, inactive constraints will be dropped (corresponding multipliers
6866  will be decreased). Ideally, you should see 10-1000x improvement in
6867  constraint handling (constraint violation is reduced).
6868 
6869 * if you see that algorithm converges to vicinity of solution, but
6870  additional outer iterations do not refine solution, it may mean that
6871  algorithm is unstable - it wanders around true solution, but can not
6872  approach it. Sometimes algorithm may be stabilized by increasing Rho one
6873  more time, making it 5x or 10x larger.
6874 
6875 SCALING OF CONSTRAINTS [IMPORTANT]
6876 
6877 AUL optimizer scales variables according to scale specified by
6878 MinNLCSetScale() function, so it can handle problems with badly scaled
6879 variables (as long as we KNOW their scales). However, because function
6880 being optimized is a mix of original function and constraint-dependent
6881 penalty functions, it is important to rescale both variables AND
6882 constraints.
6883 
6884 Say, if you minimize f(x)=x^2 subject to 1000000*x>=0, then you have
6885 constraint whose scale is different from that of target function (another
6886 example is 0.000001*x>=0). It is also possible to have constraints whose
6887 scales are misaligned: 1000000*x0>=0, 0.000001*x1<=0. Inappropriate
6888 scaling may ruin convergence because minimizing x^2 subject to x>=0 is NOT
6889 same as minimizing it subject to 1000000*x>=0.
6890 
6891 Because we know coefficients of boundary/linear constraints, we can
6892 automatically rescale and normalize them. However, there is no way to
6893 automatically rescale nonlinear constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x) - they are
6894 black boxes.
6895 
6896 It means that YOU are the one who is responsible for correct scaling of
6897 nonlinear constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x). We recommend you to rescale
6898 nonlinear constraints in such way that I-th component of dG/dX (or dH/dx)
6899 has magnitude approximately equal to 1/S[i] (where S is a scale set by
6900 MinNLCSetScale() function).
6901 
6902 WHAT IF IT DOES NOT CONVERGE?
6903 
6904 It is possible that AUL algorithm fails to converge to precise values of
6905 Lagrange multipliers. It stops somewhere around true solution, but candidate
6906 point is still too far from solution, and some constraints are violated.
6907 Such kind of failure is specific for Lagrangian algorithms - technically,
6908 they stop at some point, but this point is not constrained solution.
6909 
6910 There are exist several reasons why algorithm may fail to converge:
6911 a) too loose stopping criteria for inner iteration
6912 b) degenerate, redundant constraints
6913 c) target function has unconstrained extremum exactly at the boundary of
6914  some constraint
6915 d) numerical noise in the target function
6916 
6917 In all these cases algorithm is unstable - each outer iteration results in
6918 large and almost random step which improves handling of some constraints,
6919 but violates other ones (ideally outer iterations should form a sequence
6920 of progressively decreasing steps towards solution).
6921 
6922 First reason possible is that too loose stopping criteria for inner
6923 iteration were specified. Augmented Lagrangian algorithm solves a sequence
6924 of intermediate problems, and requries each of them to be solved with high
6925 precision. Insufficient precision results in incorrect update of Lagrange
6926 multipliers.
6927 
6928 Another reason is that you may have specified degenerate constraints: say,
6929 some constraint was repeated twice. In most cases AUL algorithm gracefully
6930 handles such situations, but sometimes it may spend too much time figuring
6931 out subtle degeneracies in constraint matrix.
6932 
6933 Third reason is tricky and hard to diagnose. Consider situation when you
6934 minimize f=x^2 subject to constraint x>=0. Unconstrained extremum is
6935 located exactly at the boundary of constrained area. In this case
6936 algorithm will tend to oscillate between negative and positive x. Each
6937 time it stops at x<0 it "reinforces" constraint x>=0, and each time it is
6938 bounced to x>0 it "relaxes" constraint (and is attracted to x<0).
6939 
6940 Such situation sometimes happens in problems with hidden symetries.
6941 Algorithm is got caught in a loop with Lagrange multipliers being
6942 continuously increased/decreased. Luckily, such loop forms after at least
6943 three iterations, so this problem can be solved by DECREASING number of
6944 outer iterations down to 1-2 and increasing penalty coefficient Rho as
6945 much as possible.
6946 
6947 Final reason is numerical noise. AUL algorithm is robust against moderate
6948 noise (more robust than, say, active set methods), but large noise may
6949 destabilize algorithm.
6950 
6951  -- ALGLIB --
6952  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
6953 *************************************************************************/
6954 void minnlcsetalgoaul(const minnlcstate &state, const double rho, const ae_int_t itscnt, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6955 
6956 
6957 /*************************************************************************
6958 This function tells MinNLC optimizer to use SLP (Successive Linear
6959 Programming) algorithm for nonlinearly constrained optimization. This
6960 algorithm is a slight modification of one described in "A Linear
6961 programming-based optimization algorithm for solving nonlinear programming
6962 problems" (2010) by Claus Still and Tapio Westerlund.
6963 
6964 Despite its name ("linear" = "first order method") this algorithm performs
6965 steps similar to that of conjugate gradients method; internally it uses
6966 orthogonality/conjugacy requirement for subsequent steps which makes it
6967 closer to second order methods in terms of convergence speed.
6968 
6969 This algorithm has following nice properties:
6970 * no parameters to tune
6971 * no convexity requirements for target function or constraints
6972 * initial point can be infeasible
6973 * algorithm respects box constraints in all intermediate points (it does
6974  not even evaluate function outside of box constrained area)
6975 * once linear constraints are enforced, algorithm will not violate them
6976 * no such guarantees can be provided for nonlinear constraints, but once
6977  nonlinear constraints are enforced, algorithm will try to respect them
6978  as much as possible
6979 * numerical differentiation does not violate box constraints (although
6980  general linear and nonlinear ones can be violated)
6981 
6982 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6983  State - structure which stores algorithm state
6984 
6985  -- ALGLIB --
6986  Copyright 02.04.2018 by Bochkanov Sergey
6987 *************************************************************************/
6988 void minnlcsetalgoslp(const minnlcstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6989

6991 /*************************************************************************
6992 This function turns on/off reporting.
6993 
6994 INPUT PARAMETERS:
6995  State - structure which stores algorithm state
6996  NeedXRep- whether iteration reports are needed or not
6997 
6998 If NeedXRep is True, algorithm will call rep() callback function if it is
6999 provided to MinNLCOptimize().
7000 
7001 NOTE: algorithm passes two parameters to rep() callback - current point
7002  and penalized function value at current point. Important - function
7003  value which is returned is NOT function being minimized. It is sum
7004  of the value of the function being minimized - and penalty term.
7005 
7006  -- ALGLIB --
7007  Copyright 28.11.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
7008 *************************************************************************/
7009 void minnlcsetxrep(const minnlcstate &state, const bool needxrep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7022

7024  state - algorithm state

7028  and Jacobian jac at given point x

7035 NOTES:
7036 
7037 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
7038  (analytical) user-supplied Jacobian, and one which uses only function
7039  vector and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
7040  gradient.
7041 
7042  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
7043  you should choose appropriate variant of MinNLCOptimize() - one which
7044  accepts function AND Jacobian or one which accepts ONLY function.
7045 
7046  Be careful to choose variant of MinNLCOptimize() which corresponds to
7047  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
7048  callback (function/gradient) passed to MinNLCOptimize() and specific
7049  function used to create optimizer.
7050 
7051 
7052  | USER PASSED TO MinNLCOptimize()
7053  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
7054  ------------------------------------------------------------
7055  MinNLCCreateF() | works FAILS
7056  MinNLCCreate() | FAILS works
7057 
7058  Here "FAILS" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
7059  function and MinNLCOptimize() version. Attemps to use such
7060  combination will lead to exception. Either you did not pass gradient
7061  when it WAS needed or you passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
7062 
7063  -- ALGLIB --
7064  Copyright 06.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey

7149 
7150 
7151 /*************************************************************************
7152 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
7153 gradient:
7154 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
7155 * MinNLCOptimize() is called
7156 * prior to actual optimization, for each component of parameters being
7157  optimized X[i] algorithm performs following steps:
7158  * two trial steps are made to X[i]-TestStep*S[i] and X[i]+TestStep*S[i],
7159  where X[i] is i-th component of the initial point and S[i] is a scale
7160  of i-th parameter
7161  * F(X) is evaluated at these trial points
7162  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
7163  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
7164  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
7165  point
7166  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
7167  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
7168  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative,
7169  and Rep.FuncIdx is set to index of the function.
7170 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
7171 
7172 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) gradient evaluations. It
7173  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
7174  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
7175  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
7176  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided by
7177  some third party).
7178 
7179 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
7180  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
7181  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
7182  parameters by means of setting scale with MinNLCSetScale().
7183 
7184 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
7185  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
7186  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
7187  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
7188  function.
7189 
7190 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7191  State - structure used to store algorithm state
7192  TestStep - verification step:
7193  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
7194  * TestStep>0 activates verification
7195 
7196  -- ALGLIB --
7197  Copyright 15.06.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
7198 *************************************************************************/
7199 void minnlcsetgradientcheck(const minnlcstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7200 #endif
7201 
7202 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINNS) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
7203 /*************************************************************************
7204  NONSMOOTH NONCONVEX OPTIMIZATION
7205  SUBJECT TO BOX/LINEAR/NONLINEAR-NONSMOOTH CONSTRAINTS
7206 
7207 DESCRIPTION:
7208 
7209 The subroutine minimizes function F(x) of N arguments subject to any
7210 combination of:
7211 * bound constraints
7212 * linear inequality constraints
7213 * linear equality constraints
7214 * nonlinear equality constraints Gi(x)=0
7215 * nonlinear inequality constraints Hi(x)<=0
7216 
7217 IMPORTANT: see MinNSSetAlgoAGS for important information on performance
7218  restrictions of AGS solver.
7219 
7220 REQUIREMENTS:
7221 * starting point X0 must be feasible or not too far away from the feasible
7222  set
7223 * F(), G(), H() are continuous, locally Lipschitz and continuously (but
7224  not necessarily twice) differentiable in an open dense subset of R^N.
7225  Functions F(), G() and H() may be nonsmooth and non-convex.
7226  Informally speaking, it means that functions are composed of large
7227  differentiable "patches" with nonsmoothness having place only at the
7228  boundaries between these "patches".
7229  Most real-life nonsmooth functions satisfy these requirements. Say,
7230  anything which involves finite number of abs(), min() and max() is very
7231  likely to pass the test.
7232  Say, it is possible to optimize anything of the following:
7233  * f=abs(x0)+2*abs(x1)
7234  * f=max(x0,x1)
7235  * f=sin(max(x0,x1)+abs(x2))
7236 * for nonlinearly constrained problems: F() must be bounded from below
7237  without nonlinear constraints (this requirement is due to the fact that,
7238  contrary to box and linear constraints, nonlinear ones require special
7239  handling).
7240 * user must provide function value and gradient for F(), H(), G() at all
7241  points where function/gradient can be calculated. If optimizer requires
7242  value exactly at the boundary between "patches" (say, at x=0 for f=abs(x)),
7243  where gradient is not defined, user may resolve tie arbitrarily (in our
7244  case - return +1 or -1 at its discretion).
7245 * NS solver supports numerical differentiation, i.e. it may differentiate
7246  your function for you, but it results in 2N increase of function
7247  evaluations. Not recommended unless you solve really small problems. See
7248  minnscreatef() for more information on this functionality.
7249 
7250 USAGE:
7251 
7252 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinNSCreate() call and chooses
7253  what NLC solver to use. There is some solver which is used by default,
7254  with default settings, but you should NOT rely on default choice. It
7255  may change in future releases of ALGLIB without notice, and no one can
7256  guarantee that new solver will be able to solve your problem with
7257  default settings.
7258 
7259  From the other side, if you choose solver explicitly, you can be pretty
7260  sure that it will work with new ALGLIB releases.
7261 
7262  In the current release following solvers can be used:
7263  * AGS solver (activated with MinNSSetAlgoAGS() function)
7264 
7265 2. User adds boundary and/or linear and/or nonlinear constraints by means
7266  of calling one of the following functions:
7267  a) MinNSSetBC() for boundary constraints
7268  b) MinNSSetLC() for linear constraints
7269  c) MinNSSetNLC() for nonlinear constraints
7270  You may combine (a), (b) and (c) in one optimization problem.
7271 
7272 3. User sets scale of the variables with MinNSSetScale() function. It is
7273  VERY important to set scale of the variables, because nonlinearly
7274  constrained problems are hard to solve when variables are badly scaled.
7275 
7276 4. User sets stopping conditions with MinNSSetCond().
7277 
7278 5. Finally, user calls MinNSOptimize() function which takes algorithm
7279  state and pointer (delegate, etc) to callback function which calculates
7280  F/G/H.
7281 
7282 7. User calls MinNSResults() to get solution
7283 
7284 8. Optionally user may call MinNSRestartFrom() to solve another problem
7285  with same N but another starting point. MinNSRestartFrom() allows to
7286  reuse already initialized structure.
7287 
7288 
7289 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7290  N - problem dimension, N>0:
7291  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
7292  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
7293  X - starting point, array[N]:
7294  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
7295  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
7296  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
7297  approximation.
7298 
7299 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
7300  State - structure stores algorithm state
7301 
7302 NOTE: minnscreatef() function may be used if you do not have analytic
7303  gradient. This function creates solver which uses numerical
7304  differentiation with user-specified step.
7305 
7306  -- ALGLIB --
7307  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7308 *************************************************************************/
7309 void minnscreate(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minnsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7310 void minnscreate(const real_1d_array &x, minnsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7312 
7313 /*************************************************************************
7314 Version of minnscreatef() which uses numerical differentiation. I.e., you
7315 do not have to calculate derivatives yourself. However, this version needs
7316 2N times more function evaluations.
7317 
7318 2-point differentiation formula is used, because more precise 4-point
7319 formula is unstable when used on non-smooth functions.
7320 
7321 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7322  N - problem dimension, N>0:
7323  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
7324  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
7325  X - starting point, array[N]:
7326  * it is better to set X to a feasible point
7327  * but X can be infeasible, in which case algorithm will try
7328  to find feasible point first, using X as initial
7329  approximation.
7330  DiffStep- differentiation step, DiffStep>0. Algorithm performs
7331  numerical differentiation with step for I-th variable
7332  being equal to DiffStep*S[I] (here S[] is a scale vector,
7333  set by minnssetscale() function).
7334  Do not use too small steps, because it may lead to
7335  catastrophic cancellation during intermediate calculations.
7336 
7337 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
7338  State - structure stores algorithm state
7339 
7340  -- ALGLIB --
7341  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7342 *************************************************************************/
7343 void minnscreatef(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minnsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7344 void minnscreatef(const real_1d_array &x, const double diffstep, minnsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7345 
7346 
7347 /*************************************************************************
7348 This function sets boundary constraints.
7349 
7350 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
7351 They are preserved after algorithm restart with minnsrestartfrom().
7352 
7353 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7354  State - structure stores algorithm state
7355  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
7356  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
7357  very small number or -INF.
7358  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
7359  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
7360  very large number or +INF.
7361 
7362 NOTE 1: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
7363 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
7364 
7365 NOTE 2: AGS solver has following useful properties:
7366 * bound constraints are always satisfied exactly
7367 * function is evaluated only INSIDE area specified by bound constraints,
7368  even when numerical differentiation is used (algorithm adjusts nodes
7369  according to boundary constraints)
7370 
7371  -- ALGLIB --
7372  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7373 *************************************************************************/
7374 void minnssetbc(const minnsstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7375 
7376 
7377 /*************************************************************************
7378 This function sets linear constraints.
7379 
7380 Linear constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
7381 They are preserved after algorithm restart with minnsrestartfrom().
7382 
7383 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7384  State - structure previously allocated with minnscreate() call.
7385  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
7386  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
7387  or inequality (see below):
7388  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
7389  * last element corresponds to the right part.
7390  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
7391  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
7392  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
7393  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
7394  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
7395  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
7396  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
7397  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
7398 
7399 NOTE: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately:
7400 
7401 * there always exists some minor violation (about current sampling radius
7402  in magnitude during optimization, about EpsX in the solution) due to use
7403  of penalty method to handle constraints.
7404 * numerical differentiation, if used, may lead to function evaluations
7405  outside of the feasible area, because algorithm does NOT change
7406  numerical differentiation formula according to linear constraints.
7407 
7408 If you want constraints to be satisfied exactly, try to reformulate your
7409 problem in such manner that all constraints will become boundary ones
7410 (this kind of constraints is always satisfied exactly, both in the final
7411 solution and in all intermediate points).
7412 
7413  -- ALGLIB --
7414  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7415 *************************************************************************/
7416 void minnssetlc(const minnsstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7417 void minnssetlc(const minnsstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7418 
7419 
7420 /*************************************************************************
7421 This function sets nonlinear constraints.
7422 
7423 In fact, this function sets NUMBER of nonlinear constraints. Constraints
7424 itself (constraint functions) are passed to minnsoptimize() method. This
7425 method requires user-defined vector function F[] and its Jacobian J[],
7426 where:
7427 * first component of F[] and first row of Jacobian J[] correspond to
7428  function being minimized
7429 * next NLEC components of F[] (and rows of J) correspond to nonlinear
7430  equality constraints G_i(x)=0
7431 * next NLIC components of F[] (and rows of J) correspond to nonlinear
7432  inequality constraints H_i(x)<=0
7433 
7434 NOTE: you may combine nonlinear constraints with linear/boundary ones. If
7435  your problem has mixed constraints, you may explicitly specify some
7436  of them as linear ones. It may help optimizer to handle them more
7437  efficiently.
7438 
7439 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7440  State - structure previously allocated with minnscreate() call.
7441  NLEC - number of Non-Linear Equality Constraints (NLEC), >=0
7442  NLIC - number of Non-Linear Inquality Constraints (NLIC), >=0
7443 
7444 NOTE 1: nonlinear constraints are satisfied only approximately! It is
7445  possible that algorithm will evaluate function outside of
7446  the feasible area!
7447 
7448 NOTE 2: algorithm scales variables according to scale specified by
7449  minnssetscale() function, so it can handle problems with badly
7450  scaled variables (as long as we KNOW their scales).
7451 
7452  However, there is no way to automatically scale nonlinear
7453  constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x). Inappropriate scaling of Gi/Hi may
7454  ruin convergence. Solving problem with constraint "1000*G0(x)=0"
7455  is NOT same as solving it with constraint "0.001*G0(x)=0".
7456 
7457  It means that YOU are the one who is responsible for correct
7458  scaling of nonlinear constraints Gi(x) and Hi(x). We recommend you
7459  to scale nonlinear constraints in such way that I-th component of
7460  dG/dX (or dH/dx) has approximately unit magnitude (for problems
7461  with unit scale) or has magnitude approximately equal to 1/S[i]
7462  (where S is a scale set by minnssetscale() function).
7463 
7464 NOTE 3: nonlinear constraints are always hard to handle, no matter what
7465  algorithm you try to use. Even basic box/linear constraints modify
7466  function curvature by adding valleys and ridges. However,
7467  nonlinear constraints add valleys which are very hard to follow
7468  due to their "curved" nature.
7469 
7470  It means that optimization with single nonlinear constraint may be
7471  significantly slower than optimization with multiple linear ones.
7472  It is normal situation, and we recommend you to carefully choose
7473  Rho parameter of minnssetalgoags(), because too large value may
7474  slow down convergence.
7475 
7476 
7477  -- ALGLIB --
7478  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7479 *************************************************************************/
7480 void minnssetnlc(const minnsstate &state, const ae_int_t nlec, const ae_int_t nlic, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
7481

7483 /*************************************************************************
7484 This function sets stopping conditions for iterations of optimizer.
7485 
7486 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7487  State - structure which stores algorithm state
7488  EpsX - >=0
7489  The AGS solver finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
7490  sampling radius decreases below EpsX.
7491  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
7492  iterations is unlimited.
7493 
7494 Passing EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to automatic
7495 stopping criterion selection. We do not recommend you to rely on default
7496 choice in production code.
7497 
7498  -- ALGLIB --
7499  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7500 *************************************************************************/
7501 void minnssetcond(const minnsstate &state, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7504 /*************************************************************************
7505 This function sets scaling coefficients for NLC optimizer.
7506 
7507 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
7508 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
7509 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
7510 a) "how large" the variable is
7511 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
7512 
7513 Scaling is also used by finite difference variant of the optimizer - step
7514 along I-th axis is equal to DiffStep*S[I].
7515 
7516 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7517  State - structure stores algorithm state
7518  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
7519  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
7520 
7521  -- ALGLIB --
7522  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7523 *************************************************************************/
7524 void minnssetscale(const minnsstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7526 
7527 /*************************************************************************
7528 This function tells MinNS unit to use AGS (adaptive gradient sampling)
7529 algorithm for nonsmooth constrained optimization. This algorithm is a
7530 slight modification of one described in "An Adaptive Gradient Sampling
7531 Algorithm for Nonsmooth Optimization" by Frank E. Curtisy and Xiaocun Quez.
7532 
7533 This optimizer has following benefits and drawbacks:
7534 + robustness; it can be used with nonsmooth and nonconvex functions.
7535 + relatively easy tuning; most of the metaparameters are easy to select.
7536 - it has convergence of steepest descent, slower than CG/LBFGS.
7537 - each iteration involves evaluation of ~2N gradient values and solution
7538  of 2Nx2N quadratic programming problem, which limits applicability of
7539  algorithm by small-scale problems (up to 50-100).
7540 
7541 IMPORTANT: this algorithm has convergence guarantees, i.e. it will
7542  steadily move towards some stationary point of the function.
7543 
7544  However, "stationary point" does not always mean "solution".
7545  Nonsmooth problems often have "flat spots", i.e. areas where
7546  function do not change at all. Such "flat spots" are stationary
7547  points by definition, and algorithm may be caught here.
7548 
7549  Nonsmooth CONVEX tasks are not prone to this problem. Say, if
7550  your function has form f()=MAX(f0,f1,...), and f_i are convex,
7551  then f() is convex too and you have guaranteed convergence to
7552  solution.
7553 
7554 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7555  State - structure which stores algorithm state
7556  Radius - initial sampling radius, >=0.
7557 
7558  Internally multiplied by vector of per-variable scales
7559  specified by minnssetscale()).
7560 
7561  You should select relatively large sampling radius, roughly
7562  proportional to scaled length of the first steps of the
7563  algorithm. Something close to 0.1 in magnitude should be
7564  good for most problems.
7565 
7566  AGS solver can automatically decrease radius, so too large
7567  radius is not a problem (assuming that you won't choose
7568  so large radius that algorithm will sample function in
7569  too far away points, where gradient value is irrelevant).
7570 
7571  Too small radius won't cause algorithm to fail, but it may
7572  slow down algorithm (it may have to perform too short
7573  steps).
7574  Penalty - penalty coefficient for nonlinear constraints:
7575  * for problem with nonlinear constraints should be some
7576  problem-specific positive value, large enough that
7577  penalty term changes shape of the function.
7578  Starting from some problem-specific value penalty
7579  coefficient becomes large enough to exactly enforce
7580  nonlinear constraints; larger values do not improve
7581  precision.
7582  Increasing it too much may slow down convergence, so you
7583  should choose it carefully.
7584  * can be zero for problems WITHOUT nonlinear constraints
7585  (i.e. for unconstrained ones or ones with just box or
7586  linear constraints)
7587  * if you specify zero value for problem with at least one
7588  nonlinear constraint, algorithm will terminate with
7589  error code -1.
7590 
7591 ALGORITHM OUTLINE
7592 
7593 The very basic outline of unconstrained AGS algorithm is given below:
7594 
7595 0. If sampling radius is below EpsX or we performed more then MaxIts
7596  iterations - STOP.
7597 1. sample O(N) gradient values at random locations around current point;
7598  informally speaking, this sample is an implicit piecewise linear model
7599  of the function, although algorithm formulation does not mention that
7600  explicitly
7601 2. solve quadratic programming problem in order to find descent direction
7602 3. if QP solver tells us that we are near solution, decrease sampling
7603  radius and move to (0)
7604 4. perform backtracking line search
7605 5. after moving to new point, goto (0)
7606 
7607 As for the constraints:
7608 * box constraints are handled exactly by modification of the function
7609  being minimized
7610 * linear/nonlinear constraints are handled by adding L1 penalty. Because
7611  our solver can handle nonsmoothness, we can use L1 penalty function,
7612  which is an exact one (i.e. exact solution is returned under such
7613  penalty).
7614 * penalty coefficient for linear constraints is chosen automatically;
7615  however, penalty coefficient for nonlinear constraints must be specified
7616  by user.
7617 
7618  -- ALGLIB --
7619  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7620 *************************************************************************/
7621 void minnssetalgoags(const minnsstate &state, const double radius, const double penalty, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7640 /*************************************************************************
7641 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
7642 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
7643 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
7644 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
7645 submitted and returns error code 8 (successful termination).
7646 
7647 INPUT PARAMETERS:
7648  State - optimizer structure
7649 
7650 NOTE: after request for termination optimizer may perform several
7651  additional calls to user-supplied callbacks. It does NOT guarantee
7652  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
7653  will be discarded later.
7654 
7655 NOTE: calling this function on optimizer which is NOT running will have no
7656  effect.
7657 
7658 NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
7659  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
7660 
7661  -- ALGLIB --
7662  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7663 *************************************************************************/
7664 void minnsrequesttermination(const minnsstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7675 /*************************************************************************
7676 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
7677 
7678 These functions accept following parameters:
7679  state - algorithm state
7680  fvec - callback which calculates function vector fi[]
7681  at given point x
7682  jac - callback which calculates function vector fi[]
7683  and Jacobian jac at given point x
7684  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
7685  can be NULL
7686  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
7687  can be NULL
7688 
7689 
7690 NOTES:
7691 
7692 1. This function has two different implementations: one which uses exact
7693  (analytical) user-supplied Jacobian, and one which uses only function
7694  vector and numerically differentiates function in order to obtain
7695  gradient.
7696 
7697  Depending on the specific function used to create optimizer object
7698  you should choose appropriate variant of minnsoptimize() - one which
7699  accepts function AND Jacobian or one which accepts ONLY function.
7700 
7701  Be careful to choose variant of minnsoptimize() which corresponds to
7702  your optimization scheme! Table below lists different combinations of
7703  callback (function/gradient) passed to minnsoptimize() and specific
7704  function used to create optimizer.
7705 
7706 
7707  | USER PASSED TO minnsoptimize()
7708  CREATED WITH | function only | function and gradient
7709  ------------------------------------------------------------
7710  minnscreatef() | works FAILS
7711  minnscreate() | FAILS works
7712 
7713  Here "FAILS" denotes inappropriate combinations of optimizer creation
7714  function and minnsoptimize() version. Attemps to use such
7715  combination will lead to exception. Either you did not pass gradient
7716  when it WAS needed or you passed gradient when it was NOT needed.
7717 
7718  -- ALGLIB --
7719  Copyright 18.05.2015 by Bochkanov Sergey
7720 
7721 *************************************************************************/

7725  void *ptr = NULL,
7726  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

7906 /*************************************************************************

7916  can be NULL

7960 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MINLM) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
7961 /*************************************************************************
7962  IMPROVED LEVENBERG-MARQUARDT METHOD FOR
7963  NON-LINEAR LEAST SQUARES OPTIMIZATION
7964 
7965 DESCRIPTION:
7966 This function is used to find minimum of function which is represented as
7967 sum of squares:
7968  F(x) = f[0]^2(x[0],...,x[n-1]) + ... + f[m-1]^2(x[0],...,x[n-1])
7969 using value of function vector f[] and Jacobian of f[].
7970 
7971 
7972 REQUIREMENTS:
7973 This algorithm will request following information during its operation:
7974 
7975 * function vector f[] at given point X
7976 * function vector f[] and Jacobian of f[] (simultaneously) at given point
7977 
7978 There are several overloaded versions of MinLMOptimize() function which
7979 correspond to different LM-like optimization algorithms provided by this
7980 unit. You should choose version which accepts fvec() and jac() callbacks.
7981 First one is used to calculate f[] at given point, second one calculates
7982 f[] and Jacobian df[i]/dx[j].
7983 
7984 You can try to initialize MinLMState structure with VJ function and then
7985 use incorrect version of MinLMOptimize() (for example, version which
7986 works with general form function and does not provide Jacobian), but it
7987 will lead to exception being thrown after first attempt to calculate
7988 Jacobian.
7989 
7990 
7991 USAGE:
7992 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinLMCreateVJ() call
7993 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinLMSetCond(), MinLMSetStpMax() and
7994  other functions
7995 3. User calls MinLMOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
7996  callback functions.
7997 4. User calls MinLMResults() to get solution
7998 5. Optionally, user may call MinLMRestartFrom() to solve another problem
7999  with same N/M but another starting point and/or another function.
8000  MinLMRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
8001 
8002 
8003 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8004  N - dimension, N>1
8005  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
8006  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
8007  M - number of functions f[i]
8008  X - initial solution, array[0..N-1]
8009 
8010 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8011  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8012 
8013 NOTES:
8014 1. you may tune stopping conditions with MinLMSetCond() function
8015 2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
8016  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
8017  use MinLMSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps.
8018 
8019  -- ALGLIB --
8020  Copyright 30.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
8021 *************************************************************************/
8022 void minlmcreatevj(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlmstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8023 void minlmcreatevj(const ae_int_t m, const real_1d_array &x, minlmstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8032 sum of squares:
8033  F(x) = f[0]^2(x[0],...,x[n-1]) + ... + f[m-1]^2(x[0],...,x[n-1])

8091 /*************************************************************************
8092  LEVENBERG-MARQUARDT-LIKE METHOD FOR NON-LINEAR OPTIMIZATION
8093 
8094 DESCRIPTION:
8095 This function is used to find minimum of general form (not "sum-of-
8096 -squares") function
8097  F = F(x[0], ..., x[n-1])
8098 using its gradient and Hessian. Levenberg-Marquardt modification with
8099 L-BFGS pre-optimization and internal pre-conditioned L-BFGS optimization
8100 after each Levenberg-Marquardt step is used.
8101 
8102 
8103 REQUIREMENTS:
8104 This algorithm will request following information during its operation:
8105 
8106 * function value F at given point X
8107 * F and gradient G (simultaneously) at given point X
8108 * F, G and Hessian H (simultaneously) at given point X
8109 
8110 There are several overloaded versions of MinLMOptimize() function which
8111 correspond to different LM-like optimization algorithms provided by this
8112 unit. You should choose version which accepts func(), grad() and hess()
8113 function pointers. First pointer is used to calculate F at given point,
8114 second one calculates F(x) and grad F(x), third one calculates F(x),
8115 grad F(x), hess F(x).
8116 
8117 You can try to initialize MinLMState structure with FGH-function and then
8118 use incorrect version of MinLMOptimize() (for example, version which does
8119 not provide Hessian matrix), but it will lead to exception being thrown
8120 after first attempt to calculate Hessian.
8121 
8122 
8123 USAGE:
8124 1. User initializes algorithm state with MinLMCreateFGH() call
8125 2. User tunes solver parameters with MinLMSetCond(), MinLMSetStpMax() and
8126  other functions
8127 3. User calls MinLMOptimize() function which takes algorithm state and
8128  pointers (delegates, etc.) to callback functions.
8129 4. User calls MinLMResults() to get solution
8130 5. Optionally, user may call MinLMRestartFrom() to solve another problem
8131  with same N but another starting point and/or another function.
8132  MinLMRestartFrom() allows to reuse already initialized structure.
8133 
8134 
8135 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8136  N - dimension, N>1
8137  * if given, only leading N elements of X are used
8138  * if not given, automatically determined from size of X
8139  X - initial solution, array[0..N-1]
8140 
8141 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8142  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8143 
8144 NOTES:
8145 1. you may tune stopping conditions with MinLMSetCond() function
8146 2. if target function contains exp() or other fast growing functions, and
8147  optimization algorithm makes too large steps which leads to overflow,
8148  use MinLMSetStpMax() function to bound algorithm's steps.
8149 
8150  -- ALGLIB --
8151  Copyright 30.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
8152 *************************************************************************/
8153 void minlmcreatefgh(const ae_int_t n, const real_1d_array &x, minlmstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8157 /*************************************************************************
8158 This function sets stopping conditions for Levenberg-Marquardt optimization
8159 algorithm.
8160 
8161 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8162  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8163  EpsX - >=0
8164  The subroutine finishes its work if on k+1-th iteration
8165  the condition |v|<=EpsX is fulfilled, where:
8166  * |.| means Euclidian norm
8167  * v - scaled step vector, v[i]=dx[i]/s[i]
8168  * dx - ste pvector, dx=X(k+1)-X(k)
8169  * s - scaling coefficients set by MinLMSetScale()
8170  Recommended values: 1E-9 ... 1E-12.
8171  MaxIts - maximum number of iterations. If MaxIts=0, the number of
8172  iterations is unlimited. Only Levenberg-Marquardt
8173  iterations are counted (L-BFGS/CG iterations are NOT
8174  counted because their cost is very low compared to that of
8175  LM).
8176 
8177 Passing EpsX=0 and MaxIts=0 (simultaneously) will lead to automatic
8178 stopping criterion selection (small EpsX).
8179 
8180 NOTE: it is not recommended to set large EpsX (say, 0.001). Because LM is
8181  a second-order method, it performs very precise steps anyway.
8182 
8183  -- ALGLIB --
8184  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
8185 *************************************************************************/
8186 void minlmsetcond(const minlmstate &state, const double epsx, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8187

8189 /*************************************************************************
8190 This function turns on/off reporting.
8191 
8192 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8193  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8194  NeedXRep- whether iteration reports are needed or not
8195 
8196 If NeedXRep is True, algorithm will call rep() callback function if it is
8197 provided to MinLMOptimize(). Both Levenberg-Marquardt and internal L-BFGS
8198 iterations are reported.
8199 
8200  -- ALGLIB --
8201  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
8202 *************************************************************************/
8203 void minlmsetxrep(const minlmstate &state, const bool needxrep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8206 /*************************************************************************
8207 This function sets maximum step length
8208 
8209 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8210  State - structure which stores algorithm state
8211  StpMax - maximum step length, >=0. Set StpMax to 0.0, if you don't
8212  want to limit step length.
8213 
8214 Use this subroutine when you optimize target function which contains exp()
8215 or other fast growing functions, and optimization algorithm makes too
8216 large steps which leads to overflow. This function allows us to reject
8217 steps that are too large (and therefore expose us to the possible
8218 overflow) without actually calculating function value at the x+stp*d.
8219 
8220 NOTE: non-zero StpMax leads to moderate performance degradation because
8221 intermediate step of preconditioned L-BFGS optimization is incompatible
8222 with limits on step size.
8223 
8224  -- ALGLIB --
8225  Copyright 02.04.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
8226 *************************************************************************/
8227 void minlmsetstpmax(const minlmstate &state, const double stpmax, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8229 
8230 /*************************************************************************
8231 This function sets scaling coefficients for LM optimizer.
8232 
8233 ALGLIB optimizers use scaling matrices to test stopping conditions (step
8234 size and gradient are scaled before comparison with tolerances). Scale of
8235 the I-th variable is a translation invariant measure of:
8236 a) "how large" the variable is
8237 b) how large the step should be to make significant changes in the function
8238 
8239 Generally, scale is NOT considered to be a form of preconditioner. But LM
8240 optimizer is unique in that it uses scaling matrix both in the stopping
8241 condition tests and as Marquardt damping factor.
8242 
8243 Proper scaling is very important for the algorithm performance. It is less
8244 important for the quality of results, but still has some influence (it is
8245 easier to converge when variables are properly scaled, so premature
8246 stopping is possible when very badly scalled variables are combined with
8247 relaxed stopping conditions).
8248 
8249 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8250  State - structure stores algorithm state
8251  S - array[N], non-zero scaling coefficients
8252  S[i] may be negative, sign doesn't matter.
8253 
8254  -- ALGLIB --
8255  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8256 *************************************************************************/
8257 void minlmsetscale(const minlmstate &state, const real_1d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8258 
8259 
8260 /*************************************************************************
8261 This function sets boundary constraints for LM optimizer
8262 
8263 Boundary constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation).
8264 They are preserved until explicitly turned off with another SetBC() call.
8265 
8266 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8267  State - structure stores algorithm state
8268  BndL - lower bounds, array[N].
8269  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
8270  very small number or -INF (latter is recommended because
8271  it will allow solver to use better algorithm).
8272  BndU - upper bounds, array[N].
8273  If some (all) variables are unbounded, you may specify
8274  very large number or +INF (latter is recommended because
8275  it will allow solver to use better algorithm).
8276 
8277 NOTE 1: it is possible to specify BndL[i]=BndU[i]. In this case I-th
8278 variable will be "frozen" at X[i]=BndL[i]=BndU[i].
8279 
8280 NOTE 2: this solver has following useful properties:
8281 * bound constraints are always satisfied exactly
8282 * function is evaluated only INSIDE area specified by bound constraints
8283  or at its boundary
8284 
8285  -- ALGLIB --
8286  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8287 *************************************************************************/
8288 void minlmsetbc(const minlmstate &state, const real_1d_array &bndl, const real_1d_array &bndu, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8289 
8290 
8291 /*************************************************************************
8292 This function sets general linear constraints for LM optimizer
8293 
8294 Linear constraints are inactive by default (after initial creation). They
8295 are preserved until explicitly turned off with another minlmsetlc() call.
8296 
8297 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8298  State - structure stores algorithm state
8299  C - linear constraints, array[K,N+1].
8300  Each row of C represents one constraint, either equality
8301  or inequality (see below):
8302  * first N elements correspond to coefficients,
8303  * last element corresponds to the right part.
8304  All elements of C (including right part) must be finite.
8305  CT - type of constraints, array[K]:
8306  * if CT[i]>0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x >= C[i,n+1]
8307  * if CT[i]=0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x = C[i,n+1]
8308  * if CT[i]<0, then I-th constraint is C[i,*]*x <= C[i,n+1]
8309  K - number of equality/inequality constraints, K>=0:
8310  * if given, only leading K elements of C/CT are used
8311  * if not given, automatically determined from sizes of C/CT
8312 
8313 IMPORTANT: if you have linear constraints, it is strongly recommended to
8314  set scale of variables with minlmsetscale(). QP solver which is
8315  used to calculate linearly constrained steps heavily relies on
8316  good scaling of input problems.
8317 
8318 IMPORTANT: solvers created with minlmcreatefgh() do not support linear
8319  constraints.
8320 
8321 NOTE: linear (non-bound) constraints are satisfied only approximately -
8322  there always exists some violation due to numerical errors and
8323  algorithmic limitations.
8324 
8325 NOTE: general linear constraints add significant overhead to solution
8326  process. Although solver performs roughly same amount of iterations
8327  (when compared with similar box-only constrained problem), each
8328  iteration now involves solution of linearly constrained QP
8329  subproblem, which requires ~3-5 times more Cholesky decompositions.
8330  Thus, if you can reformulate your problem in such way this it has
8331  only box constraints, it may be beneficial to do so.
8332 
8333  -- ALGLIB --
8334  Copyright 14.01.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
8335 *************************************************************************/
8336 void minlmsetlc(const minlmstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const ae_int_t k, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8337 void minlmsetlc(const minlmstate &state, const real_2d_array &c, const integer_1d_array &ct, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8338 
8339 
8340 /*************************************************************************
8341 This function is used to change acceleration settings
8342 
8343 You can choose between three acceleration strategies:
8344 * AccType=0, no acceleration.
8345 * AccType=1, secant updates are used to update quadratic model after each
8346  iteration. After fixed number of iterations (or after model breakdown)
8347  we recalculate quadratic model using analytic Jacobian or finite
8348  differences. Number of secant-based iterations depends on optimization
8349  settings: about 3 iterations - when we have analytic Jacobian, up to 2*N
8350  iterations - when we use finite differences to calculate Jacobian.
8351 
8352 AccType=1 is recommended when Jacobian calculation cost is prohibitively
8353 high (several Mx1 function vector calculations followed by several NxN
8354 Cholesky factorizations are faster than calculation of one M*N Jacobian).
8355 It should also be used when we have no Jacobian, because finite difference
8356 approximation takes too much time to compute.
8357 
8358 Table below list optimization protocols (XYZ protocol corresponds to
8359 MinLMCreateXYZ) and acceleration types they support (and use by default).
8360 
8361 ACCELERATION TYPES SUPPORTED BY OPTIMIZATION PROTOCOLS:
8362 
8363 protocol 0 1 comment
8364 V + +
8365 VJ + +
8366 FGH +
8367 
8368 DEFAULT VALUES:
8369 
8370 protocol 0 1 comment
8371 V x without acceleration it is so slooooooooow
8372 VJ x
8373 FGH x
8374 
8375 NOTE: this function should be called before optimization. Attempt to call
8376 it during algorithm iterations may result in unexpected behavior.
8377 
8378 NOTE: attempt to call this function with unsupported protocol/acceleration
8379 combination will result in exception being thrown.
8380 
8381  -- ALGLIB --
8382  Copyright 14.10.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
8383 *************************************************************************/
8384 void minlmsetacctype(const minlmstate &state, const ae_int_t acctype, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8392 bool minlmiteration(const minlmstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8394 
8395 /*************************************************************************
8396 This family of functions is used to launcn iterations of nonlinear optimizer
8397 
8398 These functions accept following parameters:
8399  state - algorithm state
8400  func - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
8401  value func at given point x
8402  grad - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
8403  value func and gradient grad at given point x
8404  hess - callback which calculates function (or merit function)
8405  value func, gradient grad and Hessian hess at given point x
8406  fvec - callback which calculates function vector fi[]
8407  at given point x
8408  jac - callback which calculates function vector fi[]
8409  and Jacobian jac at given point x
8410  rep - optional callback which is called after each iteration
8411  can be NULL
8412  ptr - optional pointer which is passed to func/grad/hess/jac/rep
8413  can be NULL
8414 
8415 NOTES:
8416 
8417 1. Depending on function used to create state structure, this algorithm
8418  may accept Jacobian and/or Hessian and/or gradient. According to the
8419  said above, there ase several versions of this function, which accept
8420  different sets of callbacks.
8421 
8422  This flexibility opens way to subtle errors - you may create state with
8423  MinLMCreateFGH() (optimization using Hessian), but call function which
8424  does not accept Hessian. So when algorithm will request Hessian, there
8425  will be no callback to call. In this case exception will be thrown.
8426 
8427  Be careful to avoid such errors because there is no way to find them at
8428  compile time - you can see them at runtime only.
8429 
8430  -- ALGLIB --
8431  Copyright 10.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
8432 
8433 *************************************************************************/
8434 void minlmoptimize(minlmstate &state,
8435  void (*fvec)(const real_1d_array &x, real_1d_array &fi, void *ptr),
8436  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,
8437  void *ptr = NULL,
8438  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8456 void minlmoptimize(minlmstate &state,
8457  void (*fvec)(const real_1d_array &x, real_1d_array &fi, void *ptr),
8458  void (*jac)(const real_1d_array &x, real_1d_array &fi, real_2d_array &jac, void *ptr),
8459  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,
8460  void *ptr = NULL,
8461  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8487  void (*hess)(const real_1d_array &x, double &func, real_1d_array &grad, real_2d_array &hess, void *ptr),
8488  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,

8537  void (*grad)(const real_1d_array &x, double &func, real_1d_array &grad, void *ptr),
8538  void (*jac)(const real_1d_array &x, real_1d_array &fi, real_2d_array &jac, void *ptr),
8539  void (*rep)(const real_1d_array &x, double func, void *ptr) = NULL,
8540  void *ptr = NULL,
8541  const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8544 /*************************************************************************
8545 Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm results
8546 
8547 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8548  State - algorithm state
8549 
8550 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
8551  X - array[0..N-1], solution
8552  Rep - optimization report; includes termination codes and
8553  additional information. Termination codes are listed below,
8554  see comments for this structure for more info.
8555  Termination code is stored in rep.terminationtype field:
8556  * -8 optimizer detected NAN/INF values either in the
8557  function itself, or in its Jacobian
8558  * -7 derivative correctness check failed;
8559  see rep.funcidx, rep.varidx for
8560  more information.
8561  * -3 constraints are inconsistent
8562  * 2 relative step is no more than EpsX.
8563  * 5 MaxIts steps was taken
8564  * 7 stopping conditions are too stringent,
8565  further improvement is impossible
8566  * 8 terminated by user who called minlmrequesttermination().
8567  X contains point which was "current accepted" when
8568  termination request was submitted.
8569 
8570  -- ALGLIB --
8571  Copyright 10.03.2009 by Bochkanov Sergey
8572 *************************************************************************/
8573 void minlmresults(const minlmstate &state, real_1d_array &x, minlmreport &rep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8574

8580 to store X[]. If buffer size is too small, it resizes buffer. It is

8590 /*************************************************************************

8592 parameters are left unchanged.
8593

8595 must have same number of dimensions) without object reallocation penalty.
8596 
8597 INPUT PARAMETERS:

8599  allocated with MinLMCreateXXX call.
8600  X - new starting point.
8601 
8602  -- ALGLIB --
8603  Copyright 30.07.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey
8604 *************************************************************************/
8605 void minlmrestartfrom(const minlmstate &state, const real_1d_array &x, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8608 /*************************************************************************
8609 This subroutine submits request for termination of running optimizer. It
8610 should be called from user-supplied callback when user decides that it is
8611 time to "smoothly" terminate optimization process. As result, optimizer
8612 stops at point which was "current accepted" when termination request was
8613 submitted and returns error code 8 (successful termination).
8614 
8615 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8616  State - optimizer structure
8617 
8618 NOTE: after request for termination optimizer may perform several
8619  additional calls to user-supplied callbacks. It does NOT guarantee
8620  to stop immediately - it just guarantees that these additional calls
8621  will be discarded later.
8622 
8623 NOTE: calling this function on optimizer which is NOT running will have no
8624  effect.
8625 
8626 NOTE: multiple calls to this function are possible. First call is counted,
8627  subsequent calls are silently ignored.
8628 
8629  -- ALGLIB --
8630  Copyright 08.10.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
8631 *************************************************************************/
8632 void minlmrequesttermination(const minlmstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

8670 
8671 /*************************************************************************
8672 This subroutine turns on verification of the user-supplied analytic
8673 gradient:
8674 * user calls this subroutine before optimization begins
8675 * MinLMOptimize() is called
8676 * prior to actual optimization, for each function Fi and each component
8677  of parameters being optimized X[j] algorithm performs following steps:
8678  * two trial steps are made to X[j]-TestStep*S[j] and X[j]+TestStep*S[j],
8679  where X[j] is j-th parameter and S[j] is a scale of j-th parameter
8680  * if needed, steps are bounded with respect to constraints on X[]
8681  * Fi(X) is evaluated at these trial points
8682  * we perform one more evaluation in the middle point of the interval
8683  * we build cubic model using function values and derivatives at trial
8684  points and we compare its prediction with actual value in the middle
8685  point
8686  * in case difference between prediction and actual value is higher than
8687  some predetermined threshold, algorithm stops with completion code -7;
8688  Rep.VarIdx is set to index of the parameter with incorrect derivative,
8689  Rep.FuncIdx is set to index of the function.
8690 * after verification is over, algorithm proceeds to the actual optimization.
8691 
8692 NOTE 1: verification needs N (parameters count) Jacobian evaluations. It
8693  is very costly and you should use it only for low dimensional
8694  problems, when you want to be sure that you've correctly
8695  calculated analytic derivatives. You should not use it in the
8696  production code (unless you want to check derivatives provided
8697  by some third party).
8698 
8699 NOTE 2: you should carefully choose TestStep. Value which is too large
8700  (so large that function behaviour is significantly non-cubic) will
8701  lead to false alarms. You may use different step for different
8702  parameters by means of setting scale with MinLMSetScale().
8703 
8704 NOTE 3: this function may lead to false positives. In case it reports that
8705  I-th derivative was calculated incorrectly, you may decrease test
8706  step and try one more time - maybe your function changes too
8707  sharply and your step is too large for such rapidly chanding
8708  function.
8709 
8710 INPUT PARAMETERS:
8711  State - structure used to store algorithm state
8712  TestStep - verification step:
8713  * TestStep=0 turns verification off
8714  * TestStep>0 activates verification
8715 
8716  -- ALGLIB --
8717  Copyright 15.06.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
8718 *************************************************************************/
8719 void minlmsetgradientcheck(const minlmstate &state, const double teststep, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
8720 #endif
8721 }
